@NODE Distribution "Distribution"
@TOC "MAIN"

    AmiDisk does not belong to the public domain, but can be distributed
    by all the means which will be appropriate to you, in the strict
    respect of the following conditions:

	- Exemption from payment: The distribution will have to be carried
    out WITHOUT COUNTERPART, financial or different. In particular it could
    not be proposed on a waiter receiving a part of the cost of the
    communications, not more than on a diskette or sold CD more expensive
    than their purchase price.

	- Integrality: The program must be distributed accompanied by all
    the files composing the package.

	- Exceptions: @{"Roland Florac" LINK Auteur}, and only, will be
    able exceptionally to grant a permission of distribution to him derogating
    from the principles above. In particular, the inclusion of AmiDisk in
    a whole of commercially distributed software will have to be the
    written agreement object.

	- Use: This program is free (Freeware concept), you can use it as
    much as good seems to you for a personal use.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Prťsentation "Presentation"

    AmiDisk is a program written in language C (GCC version 4.0.2).

    It is a manager of files. Its operation requires system at least 4.0.
    In addition certain functions call upon Reaction (the GUI).
    Some scripts are using to AWNPipe, from William H. M. Parker. This
    program is available on AmiNet.

    This program makes it possible to work simultaneously on several files
    or drawers, each task which can take time being managed
    independently of the others (to copy, to erase...). You can profit
    from the advanced functions of system 4.0: @{"AppWindows" LINK AppWindows},
    @{"AppIcon" LINK AppIcon}...
@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "Installation"

    The program can be copied in any drawer, with your suitability,
    provided that there is enough free place. I use, for my part, the
    drawer @{b}Utilities@{ub} of the System volume.

    The configuration files are placed in ENVARC:AmiDisk drawer.

    The @{"guide" LINK Aide} file @{b}AmiDisk.guide@{ub} must be copied in this same drawer,
    if you want to profit from the on line help. You should also
    copy the ARexx and Images drawers with AmiDisk as they are
    heavily used.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Lancement "Launching the program"

	The size of the current support of the CLI (or Shell) can be
    fixed at 32 KB (normally sufficient). AmiDisk can be launched since
    the CLI or Workbench (while clicking twice on its icon).

    Launching since the CLI: type AmiDisk or Run AmiDisk

    Launching since Workbench: It is enough to click twice on the
    icon of the program.

    The number of tabs can be set using the TABS tooltype in the
    icon of the program, it can be set between 1 and 10.
	Example : TABS=7

    Note that when starting the program carries out automatically the
    script @{"Startup.AmiDisk" LINK Startup.AmiDisk} normally located in the ARexx directory.
    This script makes it possible to define functions or variables
    which will be then used by other scripts or in macros-commands.

    @{b}Displaying the logo@{ub}

    The program posts a @{"logo" LINK AmiDiskLogo.jpg/MAIN} when starting (AmiDiskLogo.jpg file),
    you can simply remove the posting of this image by removing the file
    AmiDiskLogo.jpg, the program will function nevertheless normally.
    Posting of logo lasts at least time that the program initializes
    the graphic interface, which can take a few seconds, in particular
    when multiple images must be loaded in toolbars.

    The AmiDiskLogo.jpg image can be changed with your suitability, but it
    should not change name if you want that it is posted with starting.
    The logo was drawn by HUNOPPC (nouvel.hugues@wanadoo.fr).
@ENDNODE
@NODE PrefsDisplay "Display Preferences"
@TOC Preferences

    This requester makes it possible to regulate the following parameters:

    @{b}Mode of screen@{ub}
	- To use or not the screen of Workbench
	If Workbench used:
	    - Choice of the mode of personal screen
	    - Name of the screen
	    - Cast iron screen (menus, buttons...)

    @{b}Path of the various tabs at startup@{ub}
	Ten boxes make it possible to determine whether a tab will be
	or not initialized as of the launching of the program. It is also
	possible to define the order of sorting of each tab. This order
	will be taken into account even if no way were validated by defect
	for a given tab. It is also possible which information will be
	displayed in the @{"listview" LINK ColumnsList}, and the width of the colums can be
	adjusted there.
	The Toolbar cell is used to load an external @{"toolbar" LINK BarreOutils} at
	startup.

    @{b}Various adjustments@{ub}
	- Mouse wheel step : define the nimber of lines that will be scrolled
	when using the mouse wheel. You can choose a value of 1 to 9.
	- Requesters : define the way the requesters are placed when using the
	program.
	- To use the @{"double click" LINK DoubleClick} or not (this adjustment can then be
	changed with the liking of the user).
	- Bubbles help: validate or not the assistance for each button of
	the various windows.
	- fast display: if this button is not validated the tabs are updated
	for each entry which was modified, added or removed, this involves a
	strong deceleration for certain actions, like the reading of a
	drawer in particular. When the button is not validated, posting is
	generally made at the end of an operation, like the reading of a
	drawer for example. Posting is some accelerated considerably, but
	that can some time awkward being, if the operation spends more time
	than envisaged (one can then wonder what occurs). Functions
	@{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY} and @{"REFRESH" LINK REFRESH} make it
	possible to manage this adjustment in ARexx scripts, to pass in
	addition to this adjustment in certain particular circumstances.
	- Size of the buffer of copy: this adjustment makes it possible to
	define the quantity of memory (maximum) used by the buffer managing the
	copy of files. A big size makes it possible to work more quickly but
	uses more memory. Function @{"SETBUFF" LINK SETBUFF} makes it possible
	to manage this adjustment for each tab, in an individual way.
	Note that copying some big files on a USB key is still making the
	OS crash when using a big buffer, use 32k to prevent problems.
	- Format of the date: allows to choose which will be the format of the
	date posted in the various tabs, for the files. This adjustment
	influences also the data returned by functions @{"DATE" LINK DATE}
	and @{"TIME" LINK TIME}.


    @{b}Copy in clipboard.device@{ub}
	This whole of adjustments allows to define the format of the data
	which will be copied in the clipboard.device of Amiga by using the
	small @{"Copy in clipboard" LINK CopyClip}. You can thus copy the list (all or
	partly) of a drawer, in a text processing for example.

    @{b}Main window@{ub}
	This whole of adjustments makes it possible to define
	dimensions and the site of the principal window of AmiDisk, with its
	launching. A button makes it possible to read the co-ordinates and
	dimensions of the principal window to use them. You can also choose
	the fonts there to be used to display the lists and the buttons.

    The 8 buttons in bottom of the window allow respectively:
    - to open the AmigaGuide assistance
    - to load the settings from a file
    - to restore the last settings saved in ENVARC:AmiDisk/Display
    - to take again the default settings (To initialize)
    - to save the current settings in ENVARC:AmiDisk/Display
    - to save the settings in a selected file
    - to use the current settings (saved in ENV:AmiDisk/Display)
    - to cancel the requester and to use again the current settings
@ENDNODE
@NODE ColumnsList "List format Requester"
@TOC Preferences

    This request can be called in two ways: either starting from the
    preferences, or by using function @{"REQCOLS" LINK REQCOLS}. The first
    solution makes it possible to define the values which will be used
    with the launching of the program (saved in the AmiDisk.prefs file at
    the time of the safeguard of the preferences). The second makes it
    possible to modify the width of the columns and the posting or not of
    certain columns of the list for which the function was called. The
    order of sorting can be regulated only at the time of the call
    starting from the preferences. It is necessary to carry out the
    adjustments for each tab separately.

    It is enough to enter a negative or null value in a cell so that the
    corresponding column is not displayed any more (the first column, that of
    the names, cannot however be masked). Foot-note: it is advised to
    enter a negative value rather than one zero, it is thus easy to find
    the original value, by removing the sign simply - when one wants
    redisplay a column. In addition some macros using these values do
    not function with a zero value (see @{"COLUMNS" LINK COLUMNS}).
    A button (checkmark) can be used to toggle between a positive and
    a negative value, to make the column visible or not.

    The two buttons below the cells defining the widths of the columns are
    used to fix the size of the columns at the default values (according
    to the cast iron used), whereas the second allows to use the values
    which are present at the screen (in the principal window of AmiDisk).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Classes "The classes"
@TOC Preferences

    The classes allow to recognize certain types of files and to associate
    to them one or more @{"actions" LINK Actions}.

    To define a class, you must fix the following parameters:

    - choose a name (impossible to name two classes with the same name,
    even while using different cases).
    Examples: Lha archive, Font, Image IFF.

    - choose a definition on the name (filtering). Generally this filter
    relates to the extension (last letters of the name, often
    after a point). This system, if it is simple is unfortunately
    imperfect because a file can perfectly have a name without
    relationship with its contents. This definition is optional, you can
    enter nothing there if you choose to define one or more options which
    follow, bearing on the contents of the file.

    - to characterize the contents of the file (cells Offset 1, 2 and 3).
    You can enter here from one to three criteria which will be evaluated
    to know if the contents of the file are quite correct for the required
    class. This method is slower than the preceding one, but it much more
    reliable, it is also a little more complicated to implement. These
    cells can be filled all the three, but one only or two of them can
    also be it. In all the cases each cell which will have been defined
    will have to be checked so that the type of file is recognized. The
    contents of these cells can be given in the hexadecimal or ASCII form.
    If a string is written between double quotes (") the comparaison will
    be case unsensitive, but if simple quotes are used (') the comparaison
    will be case sensitive.
    Examples:
	0,' FWS'    the first data, before the comma, define the row
		    of the first byte in the file which will have to be
		    checked, here it acts of the first byte. The
		    continuation, placed between two apostrophes,
		    constitutes a character string in ASCII, which
		    constitutes the contents of bytes 0, 1 and 2 present
		    in the file. For this example the file must thus contain
		    the three letters F, W and S in the first three bytes of
		    the file (File of the Shockwave type).
	0,"QuickFile View 4.00" In this example the string included in
		    the beginning of the file can be written with lower or
		    upper cases letters, with no difference.
	0,'-lh'
	6,2d	    This second example includes/understands two cells, the
		    first in ASCII, as for the preceding example, the second
		    into hexadecimal. Each one of these bytes must be defined
		    using two digits (0 to F). Here the sixth byte must thus
		    be equal to 2d (either thus 45 into decimal) so that the
		    file is well recognized.

    - a cell comprising a condition (AND, BUT, XOR or AND NOT) makes it
    possible to define the condition which will bind the two criteria
    relating on the test of the name, and that defining the contents.
    Generally condition AND (and) is selected, i.e. that the name must be
    correct and contents also. But GOLD (or) is also often usable.

    - the last cell makes it possible to associate an icon by defect the
    class previously definite. It is advised to use the
    SYS:Prefs/Env-Archive/Sys drawer to choose these
    icons. This choice then makes it possible to use the function
    @{"ADDICON" LINK ADDICON} under good conditions, because it will be then this
    file which will be used.


    Each of the classes can be associated to one or more @{"actions" LINK Actions}.
    The same action can be used by several classes. The list of
    the classes includes the list of the actions for each
    class (this list is a hierarchical display, whose secondary entries
    can or not be visualized).

    The actions of the same class can be moved by using the buttons
    located all in bottom of the tab, the first on the left being used
    to make go up the action selected before the preceding action,
    except if it is already the first, the following button is used
    on the contrary to make pass the action selected after that which
    follows it, if there is one of them.

    @{b}Import/Export@{ub}
    It is finally possible to export a class in a file in order to be able
    to reimport it later on on another station for example. The export and
    the importation of the classes are done by defect in the Classes drawer
    of AmiDisk. If you import a class whereas it was already present, this
    one will be updated. If an imported class calls upon nondefinite actions,
    you will have either to define these new actions, or to import them also.
    It is advised to use the name of the class to name the file which will
    be used to contain these data.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Actions "The actions"
@TOC Classes

    The actions are used to define which program will be launched for a
    file of a type determined by its class. For example it can be
    interessant to launch MultiView, PicShow or Visio to visualize an
    image. In this case it will thus be necessary to create three actions
    (for MultiView, PicShow and Visio) and to associate them the class of
    image for which these actions are interesting.

    An action is defined by the elements which follow:
    - Its name: this one must be single, it cannot have two actions
    having the same name, even while distinguishing tiny and capital.
    The name can be different from the name of the program which will be
    launched by this action, thus an action which will launch MultiView
    could be named very well Viewer, for example.

    - the command associated with the action: this one can take various
    forms, depend on @{"mode" LINK ModeAction} of the action.

    - @{"mode" LINK ModeAction}: an action can be of mode @{"cli" LINK CLI}, Workbench,
    @{"NoCLI" LINK ModeAction}, ARexx or @{"internal" LINK Internal}.

    - the path used while launching the program, necessary for certain
    programs which need their data to launch out correctly (for the modes
    CLI, NOCLI and Workbench).

    And finally, only for the commands of type CLI (or NOCLI):
    - the @{"stack" LINK StackSize} and @{"delay" LINK Delay}.

    - two cells finally make it possible to force a cooling of the tabs
    source and/or destination after the end of the action. This cooling is
    useful if the called commands add, removes or modifies files or
    drawers located in these tabs.

    Four buttons located in the bottom of the window allow respectively
    - to associate the action selected to the class selected in the list of
    the classes, on the left (arrow towards the left),
    - to create a new action,
    - of sorting all the actions alphabetically,
    - to remove the selected action.

    @{b}Import/Export@{ub}
    It is finally possible to export an action in a file in order to be
    able to reimport it later on on another station for example. The
    export and the importation of the actions are done by defect in the
    Actions drawer of AmiDisk. If you import an action whereas it was
    already present, this one will be updated. It is advised to use the
    name of the action to name the file which will be used to contain
    these data.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Internal "Internal mode actions"
@TOC Actions

    The actions, in internal mode, can use all available @{"functions" LINK Fonctions}.
    They can be used to carry out any type of action, including launching a
    task of the type Shell or Workbench by using functions @{"RUNCLI" LINK RUNCLI} and
    @{"RUNWB" LINK RUNWB}.

    It is also possible to call an ARexx script, by using function @{"CALL" LINK CALL}, while
    passing the desired parameters.
    Example:
	CALL("EditScript", FULLNAME(SOURCE, ENTRY))

    Functions @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE} and @{"ENTRY" LINK ENTRY} will generally
    make it possible to pass the necessary arguments.
    The SOURCE function gives the source tab while the ENTRY function
    gives the index of the entry being acted.
    Function @{"DEST" LINK DEST} can also be useful.
    Example :
	READHEX(SOURCE,ENTRY)                   ' Reading a file in hexadecimal
	GETDIR(SOURCE,FULLNAME(SOURCE,ENTRY))   ' Opening a drawer
	List the content of a lha archive in a window (On AmiDisk screen) :
	OUTPUT("CON:100/50/950/900/Archive_LHA/CLOSE/WAIT/SCREENAmiDisk"):RUNCLI("c:lha v "+GETNAME(SOURCE,ENTRY),4000,CURRDIR(SOURCE))
	Displaying a file using MultiView (On AmiDisk screen) :
	RUNCLI("SYS:Utilities/Multiview """+GETNAME(SOURCE,ENTRY)+""" PUBSCREEN="+SCRNAME, 10000, CURRDIR(SOURCE))
@ENDNODE
@NODE Keys "Keys Preferences"
@TOC Preferences

    This requester makes it possible to program the function keys, like
    various keys of the keyboard, and even the other keys (provided that
    they are not used by buttons).

    The button in bottom on the left makes it possible to program the keys
    other than the function keys (Letters A to Z, various figures,
    signs...), enter simply the character to define in the dedicated cell.

    Note that the definitions of the keys defined using the function
    @{"MAP" LINK MAP} are found here.

    Some macros interesting (with the key programmed in the original
    AmiDisk.prefs file):

    - to make pass the AmiDisk window in the foreground (SPACE):
    WTOFRONT
    - to make pass the window to the background (Shift-SPACE) :
    WTOBACK

    - to calculate the size of the selected drawers (or of all) (F10) :
    IF(FIRSTSEL(SOURCE) 0, CALCSIZE(SOURCE, 0), CALCSIZE(SOURCE,-1)):IF((SORT(SOURCE, -1)==1)|(SORT(SOURCE, -1)==4), SORT(SOURCE,SORT(SOURCE, -1)), 0)
    - to post the class of the selected files (in the column comment) (F9) :
    S=SOURCE:WHILE(FIRSTSEL(S) 0, SETCOMM(S, FIRSTSEL(S),GETCLASS(FULLNAME(S, FIRSTSEL(S)))), UNMARK(S, FIRSTSEL(S)))
    - to ask the removal of the entries selected, after confirmation (DEL) :
    IF(FIRSTSEL(SOURCE),IF(REQUEST("WARNING: you will destroy"+CHR(10)+"all the files selected files"+CHR(10)+"Are you sure you to want to continue?"),DELETE(SOURCE,0),0),MESSAGE("No selection in progress"))
    - to ask for the removal of the selected entries, without confirmation (Shift-DEL) :
    IF(FIRSTSEL(SOURCE),DELETE(SOURCE,0),MESSAGE("No selection in progress"))

    - to get the list of the devices (F1) :
    DEVICES(SOURCE)
    - to get the list of volumes (F2) :
    VOLUMES(SOURCE)
    - to get the list of the assigns (F3) :
    ASSIGNS(SOURCE)
    - to get an history (F4) :
    HISTORY(SOURCE)
    - to change the active tab (TAB) :
    SETTAB(IF(SOURCE<10,SOURCE+1,1))
    - to change the active tab, to the left (Shift-TAB) :
    SETTAB(IF(SOURCE>1,SOURCE-1,10))
    - to have the active tab (source) to the right (RIGHT arrow) :
    S=SOURCE:D=DEST:IF(S<6,SETTAB(D),IF(S<10,SETTAB(S+1),0))
    - to have the active tab (source) to the left (LEFT arrow) :
    S=SOURCE:IF(S>5,SETTAB(DEST),IF(S>0,SETTAB(S-1),0))
    - to select the first tab (key 1) :
    SETTAB(1)

    - to scroll the active list one line up (UP) :
    TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)-1)
    - to scroll the active list one line down (DOWN) :
    TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)+1)
    - to scroll the active list ten lines up (PageUP, Shift-UP) :
    N=TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)-10:IF(N<0,N=0,N):TOPLIST(SOURCE,N)
    - to scroll the active list ten lines down (PageDOWN, Shift-DOWN) :
    TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)+10)
    - to select the previous entry (Ctrl-UP) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,S=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),IF(S>1,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,S-1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,S-2),0)),0)
    - pour sťlectionner l'entrťe suivante (Ctrl-DOWN) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,S=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,1),IF(S<ENTRIES(SOURCE),UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,S+1),0)),0)
    - to view the top of the list (Alt-UP) :
    TOPLIST(SOURCE,0)
    - to view the end of the list (Alt-DOWN) :
    TOPLIST(SOURCE,100000)
    - to extend the zone of selection to the top (Shift-Ctrl-UP) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,S=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),IF(S>1,MARK(SOURCE,S-1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,S-2),0)),0)
    - to extend the zone of selection to the bottom (Shift-Ctrl-DOWN) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,SEL=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):WHILE((SEL>0) & (SEL<ENTRIES(SOURCE)),S=SEL:IF(TEST(SOURCE,SEL+1),SEL=SEL+1:S=SEL,SEL=0)):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,1),IF(S<ENTRIES(SOURCE),MARK(SOURCE,S+1),0)),0)
    - to select the fist entry of the list (Ctrl-Alt-UP) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,0),0)
    - to select the last entry of the list (Ctrl-Alt-DOWN) :
    IF(SOURCE>0,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)):TOPLIST(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),0)

    - to go up with the parent drawer (BACKSPACE) :
    GETDIR(SOURCE,PATHPART(CURRDIR(SOURCE)))
    -  to go up with the root directory (HOME) :
    DIR=CURRDIR(SOURCE):END=POS(":",DIR):IF(END>0,GETDIR(SOURCE,SUBS(DIR,1,END)),0)

    @{b}Import/Export@{ub}
    Two buttons located on the right of each cell being used to define the macros
    are used to import (arrow towards the left) macros or to export them (arrow
    towards the line). A request makes it possible to choose the name of the file
    in which or these data will be saved or read. The drawer by defect is the
    drawer Macros de AmiDisk.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UserMenus "User menus Preferences"
@TOC Preferences

     This tab makes it possible to define the action that will be launched
     when one of the ten programmable menus will be selected.
     You can define the title of the menu, that will be displayed in the
     menu bar, and the associated command.
     I use these menus for actions that are not often used.
     Commands can use all the available ARexx @{"functions" LINK Fonctions} , to call a
     script, use something like :
	CALL("Script name")
    Normaly, scripts have to be called without any argument, then the script
    itself handle all selected entries, if needed.

    @{b}Import/Export@{ub}
    Two buttons located on the right of each cell being used to define the menus
    are used to import (arrow towards the left) macros or to export them (arrow
    towards the line). A request makes it possible to choose the name of the file
    in which these data will be saved or read. The default drawer is the Menus
    drawer of AmiDisk. You can also import a file comprising macro (Macros drawer
    by default), the menu corresponding will use this command then, but the title
    of the menu will not be changed.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Icons Icons
@TOC BarreOutils

    The icons can use @{b}images@{ub} selected by the user. These images
    must simply be recognized by the datatypes to be able to be loaded.
    It is possible to use two images the first being posted as long as the
    user did not click on the button, the second being posted at the time
    of the action on the button. If an image could not be posted an error
    message is posted on the button, in the place of the image.

    It is possible to create buttons not using an image, with the proviso
    of specifying a @{b}label@{ub}, which will be posted in the button.
    The label can also be posted under the image, if it is given at the
    same time as an image was defined.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditButton "Buttons preferences"
@TOC BarreOutils

    Buttons can be associated to @{"images" LINK Icons} (icons) or texts.

    A @{b}line of help@{ub} can be specified, this help will be posted in
    the title bar of the window when the left button of the mouse is used.

    It is possible to define bistable buttons: those preserve their state
    (selected or not) after the action of the user. This type of button is
    useful to define the state of a particular function, like the warning
    announcing the replacement of a file at the time of a copy. Attention,
    one should not place two buttons (in the same bar or different bars)
    defining the same function, because an action on one of them will
    return the other incoherent ones compared to this one.

    When editing a button, five buttons can define the way the
    edited button will be used ;
    - Ignore busy source tab : usefull to launch a program that will
    not use any tab (to launch Tetris, for example... or open
    a Shell)
    Attention this functions works correctly only with internal command, use
    functions @{"RUNCLI" LINK RUNCLI}, @{"RUNWB" LINK RUNWB} or @{"CALL" LINK CALL} if you must launch a
    program under Shell, Workbench or a script.
    - Check valid path : the action will be launched only if the
    tab has a valid path (the tab must not be empty, or contain
    a devices, assigns, volumes or history list)
    - Check selection : the action will be launched only if the
    source tab has one (or more) selected entry.
    - Check destination tab : the action will be launched only if
    the destination tab is free.
    - Process all selected entries : the action will be launched
    for each selected entry of the source tab.
    This button must not be selected for actions in ARexx mode,
    as the scripts handle all the entries themselves. If you
    want to call a script for each entry, use an internal action,
    and use the CALL function, for example
	CALL("EditScript",FULLNAME(SOURCE,0))
    to edit each selected entry with Amitex.

    @{b}Import/Export@{ub}
    To export the data associated with a button, it is initially
    necessary to edit the button, then to click on the Export button.
    The Import button located in bottom of the edit window makes it
    possible to read the data present in a file in order to define a
    button very quickly. This button will be placed on the right bar
    of the tool bar. The default drawer is the Buttons drawer of
    AmiDisk.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ModeAction "Actions Modes"
@TOC Actions

    Actions can be associated to several modes :
    - @{"CLI" LINK CLI} : the command will be launched as under a Shell.

    -Workbench : a program will be launched as if the user double clicked
    on its icon, as using the Workbench.
    The selected entry will be passed as its argument.

    - NOCLI : this mode is analog to @{"CLI" LINK CLI} mode, except that in
    this case no console is opened, except if a redirection is given
    in command line (using the > operator).

    - ARexx : this mode call an AmiDisk ARexx @{"script" LINK Script}.
    This script must normally be placed in the AmiDisk ARexx drawer.
    It's recommended that the scripts have the .AmiDisk extension to
    their names, but this extension can be given or not in the command.
    Scripts are called with three arguments when they are launched
    to handle a specific entry :
	- the source tab number (from 1 to 10)
	- the destination tab number (from 1 to 10)
	- the entry number (from 1 to the last...)
    But they are called without any argument when they are called
    to handle all entries.

    - @{"Internal" LINK Internal} : this mode makes possible to use all the available @{"functions" LINK Fonctions}.
    Arguments are often using @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE}, @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, @{"ENTRY" LINK ENTRY} functions.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLI "CLI type action"
@TOC ModeAction

    For an action of the type CLI the call of the action will consist of a
    launching of a DOS command, as under Shell. The command must be specified
    in the cell "Command", under the list of the actions. In the majority
    of the cases it will be necessary to associate this command to arguments,
    to be able to specify to it which are the files or drawers to be
    treated. These arguments will have to be defined in the cell
    "Arguments" located below. A small button located on the right of this
    cell makes it possible to choose the standard arguments available:
	- [f]: name of the selected entry (surrounded of quotation marks)
	- [F]: complete name of the selected entry (including the name†of
	the drawer or the volume associated with the active source tab,
	surrounded of quotation marks)
	- [d]: name of the drawer or volume associated with the destination tab
	- [D]: name of the drawer or volume associated with the destination tab
	with a / at the end; if it is necessary (i.e. if it is a drawer and not a
	volume).
	- [?]: the name placed there will be selected using an Asl
	requester.
	Note that it is always necessary to place a space at the
	head of the arguments, indeed to constitute the order who will be
	carried out in the console, the order and the arguments are assembled
	in only one line, space is thus used as separator.
	Arguments created using [d] and (D] have no quotation marks, as they
	can be completed with a filename. You can add them if you think they
	are needed : "[D]".

	This type of action, when it is used, sees its outputs posted in a
    console. This one can be defined by adding a redirection to the order
    (or the arguments), for example:
	>CON:100/50/950/900/Archive_LHA/CLOSE/WAIT
	In this example the console will thus have a width of 950 pixels, a
	height of 900, will be placed at co-ordinates 100, 50, the title
	displayed in the title bar of the window will be Archive_LHA, it will
	have a button making it possible to close it with the mouse (CLOSED)
	and it will be necessary to await an action of user (WAIT) so that it
	is closed (if not it would be closed as of the end of the execution of
	the command). If there is no redirection, a console by defect is used.

    An action of this type must be associated to a @{"stack size" LINK StackSize}
    and a @{"delay" LINK Delay}.

    Examples :
	Extract an archive, listing in a window on AmiDisk screen :
	    Command   : c:lha >CON:100/50/950/900/Archive_LHA/CLOSE/WAIT/SCREENAmiDisk
	    Arguments :  x [f] "[D]"
	Decompress a PowerPacker archive :
	    Command   : c:PPUnPack
	    Arguments :  [f] [D][f]
@ENDNODE
@NODE StackSize "Size of the stack associated to a CLI type action (or NOCLI)"
@TOC ModeAction

    The size of the stack defines the size of the stack which will be
    associated to the program which will be launched at the time of the
    launching of the action. This size depends naturally on the program
    which must then be launched, consult the documentation of this program
    to know its needs. Standard DOS commands ask for only stacks of small
    size (4096 bytes often sufficient) whereas certain applications can be
    much more demanding (more than 100000 bytes and even some time much
    more). It is important not to choose a too small size, that would very
    often involve a crash of the program, or even the complete system.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Delay "Delay associated to a CLI type action (or NOCLI)"
@TOC ModeAction

    The time associated with an action of the type CLI or NOCLI is used to
    define when the console associated with a command is closed:
    - if it is equal to -1, it will be necessary that the user closes itself
    the window (that leaves him time to read what is posted there)
    - if it is null, the console is closed as soon as the program finishes
    - if it is positive, a time of as many seconds will be counted before
    closing the console.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Menus" "Les menus"
@TOC Main

	AmiDisk have two menus, usualy selected using the
    right mouse button.

	@{"Project menu " LINK Project}
	@{"Macros menu  " LINK Macros}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Project" "Project Menu"

    This menu has six entries:
	@{"Infos            " LINK Infos}     Display some informations
	@{"Copy to clipboard" LINK CopyClip}     Copy a list of drawers and/or files
	@{"New bar          " LINK "New†bar"}     Edit a new external bar
	@{"Load bar         " LINK "Load†bar"}     Load an external toolbar
	@{"Preferences      " LINK Preferences}     Preferences requester
	@{"Quit             " LINK Quit}             Stop the program.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Infos "Menu Project/Infos"
@TOC Project

    This menu causes the posting of a certain number of information:
    copyright, free quantity of memory...

       Keyboard shortcut : AMIGA-F
@ENDNODE
@NODE CopyClip "Menu Project/Copy to clipboard"
@TOC Project

    This menu makes it possible to copy a list of names of drawers and/or
    files in the clipboard of Amiga. You can then copy this list in a
    text, using a text editor. You can copy various things using a
    request:
	- the name of the file (or the drawer)
	- its size
	- bits of protection
	- the creation date (or modification)
	- the hour of creation
	- the associated comment
    You can also choose to treat only the entries of the active tab
    which are selected or all its entries. The cell "Heading drawers"
    makes it possible to announce the drawers as you
    hear it (the last Taille=Dir option makes it possible to write the Dir
    mention in the column reserved for the size, for the drawers, it
    requires that the Size cell is marked to have an effect). The choice
    of the data to be copied (by default) can be carried out in the
    @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay} requester.

    This order can succeed only if the tab source is not blocked by a
    task (ARexx script, pending command...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "New†bar" "Menu Project/New bar"
@TOC Project

    This menu makes it possible to create a new @{"toolbar" LINK BarreOutils}.
    When it is selected, an empty window is open. It is then possible
    @{"to add buttons" LINK EditBar} to this bar by editing it.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Load†bar" "Menu Project/Load bar"
@TOC Project

    This menu makes it possible to choose a file containing the
    definition of an @{"external toolbar" LINK BarreOutils} using a Asl request,
    and to post it so that it is used. You can choose very
    well one of the files included in the preferences (HigherButtons,
    CenterButtons or LowerButtons), the bar will be then identical to
    the internal but detached of the principal window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Preferences "Menu Project/Preferences"
@TOC Project

    This menu makes it possible to open a Reaction requester in order to
    manage the screen modes, the dimensions of the principal window, the
    paths opened by defect at the time of the starting of the program on
    the one hand, and on the other hand the classes defining the various
    files recognized by the program as well as the actions which can be
    associated for them. This adjustment can be called whereas certain
    tasks are proceeding (copy of files, etc...)

    It is also possible to define the commands associated with
    certain combinations with keys and the menus users (version 1.05).

    The preferences menu comprises five entries :
	- @{"    Display       " LINK PrefsDisplay}
	- @{"     Classes      " LINK Classes}
	- @{"       Keys       " LINK Keys}
	- @{"   User menus     " LINK "UserMenus"}
	- @{"   Buttons top    " LINK UserButtons}
	- @{"  Buttons center  " LINK UserButtons}
	- @{"  Buttons bottom  " LINK UserButtons}

    Each one of these menus can be associated a button by using function
    @{"REQPREFS" LINK REQPREFS}.

    Note that certain problems can occur, if you change the screen mode
    while certain tasks still run, it will be impossible to close the window
    to reopen it by taking of to account this new fashion...
@ENDNODE
@NODE Quit "Menu Project/Quit"
@TOC Project

    The program closes the main window and releases the resources
    used. However this cannot take place if there are tasks which run at
    this time there (like a copy of files).

       Keyboard shortcut : AMIGA-Q
@ENDNODE
@NODE AppIcon "AmiDisk AppIcon"
@TOC MAIN

    The concept of AppIcon (Icon of application) authorizes the reading of
    a drawer  in a very simple way, in only one action, using the mouse. As
    described, in the @{"introduction" LINK Lancement}, the program creates an icon which
    appears on the Workbench screen. This icon bears the name of AmiDisk.
    It is enough for you to drag an icon corresponding to a file or
    a drawer, using the mouse, and to make it drop on this icon so that
    this drawer is read in the active tab.

    This icon also has another function: while clicking twice above
    quickly, with the left button, you can "awake" the program if the
    window is hidden.
@ENDNODE
@NODE AppWindows "Reading drawers using AppWindow"
@TOC MAIN

    The main window is an AppWindow. Thus you can make drop the icon of
    a drawer on this window and this drawer will be read in the active
    tab.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Macros "Menu Macros"
@TOC Menus

    This menu makes it possible to use the macros-commands and ARexx
    scripts.

    This menu has the following entries:
	@{"Direct     " LINK Direct}
	@{"Call script" LINK RunScript}
	@{"New script " LINK NewScript}
	@{"Edit script" LINK EditScript}
	@{"ARexx...   " LINK Macro...}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Direct "Menu Macros/Direct"
@TOC Macros

    This menu makes it possible to carry out a @{"macro-command" LINK WritingCommands}.
    A button located on the left makes it possible to choose a command
    among those available, including those which defined by the user
    (at the end of the list). you can thus add new functions
    easily and also obtain the AmigaGuide assistance relative to a
    function by selecting it and by pressing key HELP.

    Note that the execution of the command is made by a separated task,
    leaving the process principal, which manages the AmiDisk window,
    available for other commands.

    You can cause the posting of the result of the command while making
    begin the text specifying this command with the equal sign (=).

    You can also program the function keys combined with or without
    the keys Shift, Alt and Ctrl to obtain canned macros (see @{"function keys" LINK Keys}).

    @{I}Example:@{UI}
      =4*95		    display the result of the multiplication (4 by 95)
      =FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)     display the number of the first selected file in the
			    source tab.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-;

    @{I}See also:@{UI} functions @{"EXEC" LINK EXEC}, @{"MAP" LINK MAP}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RunScript "Menu Macros/Call script"
@TOC Macros

    This menu allows the call of an ARexx script. Scripts are placed by
    default in the ARexx drawer of AmiDisk, their name comprises the
    AmiDisk extension. Scripts in fact are launched while using the
    @{"call" LINK CALL} function which launches, like all the others
    macros, a separated task, which manages its own ARexx port.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-,
@ENDNODE
@NODE "NewScript" "Menu Macros/New script"
@TOC Macros

    This menu is used to call a text editor (Amitex by default) which makes
    it possible to create a new script. It uses in fact the
    CALL("NewScript macro-order") which launches the execution of script
    @{"NewScript.AmiDisk" LINK NewScript.AmiDisk}, this one have, of course, to be
    available in the ARexx drawer. This script was written for my
    text editor (Amitex), it will have to be modified for another editor.
    It uses script edit.rexx, normally placed in REXX:, thus if Amitex is
    already charged a new window is simply open in reloading the program.
    At the time of the launching of the editor, the EmptyScript.AmiDisk
    file is loaded, a request is open to give the name of this script.
    The window is then re-elected with this name, and the error messages
    per default (at the end of the file) are also updated. The cursor is
    then placed at the site of beginning of the instructions to write by
    the user.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-N
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EditScript" "Menu Macros/Edit script"
@TOC Macros

    This menu is used to call a text editor (Amitex by default) which makes
    it possible to modify scripts. It uses in fact the CALL("EditScript") command,
    which launches the execution of script @{"EditScript.AmiDisk" LINK EditScript.AmiDisk}, this one owes of
    course being available in the ARexx drawer. This script was written
    for my text editor (Amitex), it will have to be modified for another
    editor.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-E
@ENDNODE
@NODE Macro... "Menu Macros/Macro..."
@TOC Macros

    AmiDisk has 10 menus which can be programmed with your suitability, in
    @{"preferences" LINK Preferences}. Each one of these menus can thus
    be associated to a title and a macro-command. Use simply function @{"call"LINK CALL}
    to launch an ARexx script. At the time of the call of one of
    these menus, a separate task is launched to carry out the command.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-0 ŗ 9
@ENDNODE
@NODE WritingCommands "Writing a commande line"
@TOC Macros

    The macro-commands can be carried out in local mode or by the
    intermediary of an @{"script ARexx" LINK Script}. You can refer to the
    scripts given in example, in the ARexx drawer. Those must have the
    extension "AmiDisk" to their name. Each one of these macro-commands can
    call one of the ARexx functions, or even several. Some of them require
    one or more arguments, the majority of them turn over a result. The
    program also makes it possible to handle @{"variables" LINK Variable}
    (of the types numerical or character string). Moreover you can define
    your own functions. The call of a function is done by giving its name,
    follow-up of one or more arguments, surrounded of brackets, possibly
    separated by commas.

    These expressions can comprise mathematical available @{"operators" LINK Opťrateurs}.

    Finally it should be noted that you can place a comment at the end of
    macro comprising a mathematical expression by using the apostrophe
    seen higher.
    Example:
    DELETE(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)) ' Delete the first selected entry

    Lastly, you can place several calls of functions on the same line, by
    separating them by two points.
     @{i}Example:@{ui}
	DIR=CURRDIR(SOURCE):END=POS(":",DIR):IF(END>0,GETDIR(SOURCE,SUBS(DIR,1,END)),0)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Opťrateurs "Mathematical operators available"

    The traditional mathematical operators are of course available:
	operator		  sign	 priority
	rise with a power:	    ^	   10
	division:		    /	    9
	multiplication: 	    *	    9
	modulos:		    %	    9
	addition:		    +	    8
	subtraction:		    -	    8
	logical AND:		    &	    6
	OR exclusive:		    ?	    5
	logical OR:		    |	    4
	assignment:		    =	    2

    This last operator (=) can be used to affect @{"variables" LINK Variable}.
    Ex: A=2, assigns value 2 to variable A. It should be noted
    that writing A=B=3 is not allowed, it will involve an error message
    "impossible Assignment". Use writing A=3:B=3 rather.

    Other operators:
	shift on the left: <<
	shift on the right: >>
    These two operators have a priority equalizes to 7.
	higher test: >		higher or equal test: >=
	lower test:  <		lower or equal test ; <=
	test different : <>	test equality:	      ==
    The tests return the value 1 if they are checked, 0 in the other
    cases. Their priority is equal to 3.

    There is a particular operator who in fact is not one, it is the
    sign :, this one allows in fact to separate two formulas (or more) in
    order to be able to seize several assignments of @{"variables" LINK Variable}
    in the same function. Thus you can seize A=2:B=3:C=0 in only
    one command instead of using three of them. The returned result is then
    that of the last operation carried out (0 in this example). This
    possibility can also be of an interest for a function @{"for" LINK FOR}, in
    order to carry out multiple initializations at the beginning of a loop.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Variable "Variables"
@TOC Macros

    The variables handled by AmiDisk can be of two types:
    @{B}numeric@{UB} or @{B}string of chars@{UB}. The type is
    selected at the time of the assignment, it cannot then be changed.

    To assign a value to a variable it is enough to make follow its name
    of the sign = and the value to be affected to it.

    Examples:
    A = 1
    B2 = "text string"
    A2 = "First "+B2     gives "First text string" for A2

    The @{"strings of chars" LINK Strings} must be framed by
    quotation marks if they are constants. @{"Numerical values" LINK Nombres}
    are limited to the integers (long), use ARexx to handle
    real numbers.

    The names of variables can include from 1 to 21 characters,
    they must begin with a letter, the following characters being able to
    be letters (accentuated or not), numbers or the character _.

    Examples of valid variable names:
	VAR
	DATA_TYPE
	FILE1

    Note that the program normally converts the names of functions and
    variables in capital letters when they are entered, also will not
    have there it a difference between two names like variable and
    VARIABLE (or even Variable), however in an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}, use
    the capital letters preferably because the chains
    resulting from the interpreter are not inevitably converted, and the
    program will then differentiate the names written in small letters
    and/or in capital letters.

    Warning: the variables are not usable directly with ARexx, they are
    internal with the program AmiDisk and the ARexx interpreter has his
    own variables. It is however possible to simply return a value of
    variable to the interpreter by giving his name:
    @{i}Example:@{ui} '
	NOM_VARIABLE'; v=result
    The contents of variable NOM_VARIABLE is thus transferred in
    the variable ARexx v. It is often advantageous to use internal
    variables with AmiDisk because their treatment is faster, in
    addition that can avoid the sending of certain messages between the
    interpreter and the program, which involves a profit enormous speed.

    @{b}WARNING@{ub}: the macros-commands are carried out by tasks
    independent of the main program, they are stopped when this command
    finishes, the contents of these variables are thus usable only during
    the execution time of this command. In addition each script or each
    command uses its own variables, without interference, unless using
    functions @{"SETVAR" LINK SETVAR} and @{"GETVAR" LINK GETVAR}, which give access
    to the aggregate variables.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Nombres "Numeric variables"
@TOC Maths

    The numbers handled by AmiDisk are limited to the integers. They
    are long signed integers, on 32 bits. The maximum value is
    2^31-1 (2147483647) and the minimal value -2^31 (-2147483648).
    Use the capacities of the ARexx interpreter to handle numbers
    in floating point, if needed.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Strings "Strings of chars"
@TOC Variable

    The character strings include an unspecified number of
    characters (theoretically limited only by the memory size of your
    microcomputer), while starting with the null chain which do not
    include any character. To define a character string, you
    must frame his contents by two quotation marks. If this chain
    includes itself one or more quotation marks, those must be
    doubled.

    Examples:
    "String of chars"
    ""
    "It's a quotation mark "" !"
@ENDNODE
@NODE Script "ARexx scripts structure"
@TOC Main

    ARexx scripts are ASCII files, conforming to a format allowing their
    interpretation by this software. They can include all the functions
    specific to ARexx and its libraries (you defer to their documentations
    for more precise details), like all the command supported by the
    program AmiDisk (a hundred, plus the functions possibly defined by
    your care).

    @{B}Emplacement@{UB} These scripts must be located is in the
    AmiDisk/ARexx drawer. It is advised to name them with the AmiDisk
    extension, but it is not obligatory.

    @{B}Format@{UB} These scripts must always start with a remark included
    between the characters /* and * /, as in C language.

    The AmiDisk commands must imperatively appear in capital letters. They
    are the same ones as those which are used in @{"local mode" LINK Direct},
    however their analysis by ARexx requires some precautions,
    thus these commands must imperatively be framed by apostrophes (') or
    quotation marks, in order to differentiate them from the internal
    functions with ARexx.

    @{B}Example@{UB}
    The following structure is recommended for these scripts:

/* This file show you an exemple of possible structure
for a script file called by AmiDisk, by the Macros menu */

options results     /* necessary to get macros results */

signal on error     /* to catch errors */
signal on syntax

'LANGUAGE'
if result="french.language" then fr=1
else fr=0

/* Your program have to be placed here */

exit

/* Error handler, program interruption */
syntax:
erreur=RC
if fr=1 then 'MESSAGE("Erreur de syntaxe"+CHR(10)+"en ligne 'SIGL'"+CHR(10)+"'errortext(erreur)'")'
else 'MESSAGE("Syntax error"+CHR(10)+"in line 'SIGL'"+CHR(10)+"'errortext(erreur)'")'
exit

error:
if fr=1 then 'MESSAGE("Erreur en ligne 'SIGL'")'
else 'MESSAGE("Error in line 'SIGL'")'
exit

    This example already exists in the ARexx drawer, it's called
    @{B}EmptyScript.AmiDisk@{UB}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ARexxScripts "ARexx Scripts"
@TOC MAIN

    Following scripts are described here:
	@{"AnyAction    " LINK AnyAction.AmiDisk}        @{"Archive      " LINK Archive.AmiDisk}
	@{"Cmp          " LINK Cmp.AmiDisk}        @{"CmpDrawers   " LINK CmpDrawers.AmiDisk}
	@{"CmpFiles     " LINK CmpFiles.AmiDisk}        @{"Copy         " LINK Copy.AmiDisk}
	@{"CopyNewer    " LINK CopyNewer.AmiDisk}        @{"Duplicate    " LINK Duplicate.AmiDisk}
	@{"EditScript   " LINK EditScript.AmiDisk}        @{"EmptyScript  " LINK EmptyScript.AmiDisk}
	@{"Filter       " LINK Filter.AmiDisk}        @{"FindString   " LINK FindString.AmiDisk}
	@{"LoadHistory  " LINK LoadHistory.AmiDisk}        @{"Makedir      " LINK Makedir.AmiDisk}
	@{"MapKey       " LINK MapKey.AmiDisk}        @{"MoveArchive  " LINK MoveArchive.AmiDisk}
	@{"MultiView    " LINK MultiView.AmiDisk}        @{"NewScript    " LINK NewScript.AmiDisk}
	@{"ReadASCII    " LINK ReadASCII.AmiDisk}        @{"ReadFiles    " LINK ReadFiles.AmiDisk}
	@{"ReadHexa     " LINK ReadHexa.AmiDisk}        @{"Rename       " LINK Rename.AmiDisk}
	@{"Root         " LINK Root.AmiDisk}        @{"RunWB        " LINK RunWB.AmiDisk}
	@{"SaveHistory  " LINK SaveHistory.AmiDisk}        @{"Search       " LINK Search.AmiDisk}
	@{"SelectedSize " LINK SelectedSize.AmiDisk}        @{"Startup      " LINK Startup.AmiDisk}
	@{"ToLeft       " LINK ToLeft.AmiDisk}        @{"ToRight      " LINK ToRight.AmiDisk}
	@{"Touch        " LINK Touch.AmiDisk}        @{"UnFilter     " LINK UnFilter.AmiDisk}
	@{"UnProtect    " LINK UnProtect.AmiDisk}        @{"UpdateCopy   " LINK UpdateCopy.AmiDisk}
	@{"WBInfo       " LINK WBInfo.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE AnyAction.AmiDisk "Script ARexx AnyAction.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}AnyAction.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/AnyAction.AmiDisk/MAIN} is used to launch an action
    for all selected entries (when called without any argument)
    or for one entry (script call : CALL("AnyAction",SOURCE,DEST,N)).
    The action is choosen in a requester including all defined
    actions, like defined in @{"preferences" LINK Classes}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Archive.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Archive.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Archive.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Archive.AmiDisk/MAIN} can be used to create an lha archive
    It uses the lha command, which must be present in the C: drawer. The
    files (and/or drawers) to archive must be selected in the source tab
    before the call of script. If an argument is passed to the script, it
    will be used as name for the file, if not a request will enable you to
    choose a file (by default located in the destination tab).

    Caution: if the file existed already, the files which were present
    there will be replaced.

    The execution of script can be stopped while pressing on key ESC or
    while clicking on a button using the function @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK}, whereas
    one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Cmp.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Cmp.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Cmp.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.02)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Cmp.AmiDisk/MAIN} ensures the comparison of
    files. The files of the source tab which are selected, are compared
    with those of the  destination tab comprising the same name. It uses
    the cmp command, which must of course be installed on your system. I use
    for my part the old Arp command, of 1989, which functions always
    perfectly. But it must exist more recent versions which also function.
    If a drawer is selected the command is called with the ALL option,
    which makes it possible to compare all the files included in the
    drawer. However the results of the comparison, in this case, are
    not posted that if they are incorrect, whereas they are it always in
    the case of files.

    Script can be called with three arguments:
	CALL("cmp", SOURCE, DEST, N)
    Operation is then the following, the file of row N of the source tab
    is compared with that located in the destination tab (if it
    exists).
    SOURCE and DEST tabs must have a value ranging between 1 and 10.

    The execution of script can be stopped while pressing on key ESC or
    while clicking on a button using the function BREAK, whereas
    one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CmpDrawers.AmiDisk "Script Arexx CmpDrawers.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

	@{b}CmpDrawers.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/CmpDrawers.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to compare the contents of the
    drawers source and destination. Attention, this comparison relates
    only on the names of the files and drawers, not to their creation
    date or their contents. The entries which are not present in one of
    the tabs are selected at the end of script.

	This script does not accept any argument. It could be very
    improved (test contained of the files, check dates...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE CmpFiles.AmiDisk "Script ARexx CmpFiles.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}CmpFiles.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/CmpFiles.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows to compare files contents.

    If the script is called without an argument, selected files
    of the source tab are compared with the files that have the
    same name in the destination tab.
    If a differece is found, an error message is displayed and
    the next files are not compared.
    If no difference is found a message is displayed when the
    operation is finished.
    Nota : if the script is called while only one entry is
    selected in each of the source and destination tabs
    these two entries will be compared even they have not
    the same names.

    The script can also be called with four arguments :
	CALL("CmpFiles",SOURCE,DEST,N1, N2)
	The file of row N1 of the source tab is compared with
	the file of row N2 of the destination tab.
    You can also compare two files of the same tab using this
    command :
	CALL("CmpFiles",TABX,TABX,N1,N2)
	where TABX is any tab number (usualy the SOURCE tab)

    The execution of script can be stopped while pressing on key ESC or
    while clicking on a button using the function BREAK, whereas
    one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Copy.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Copy.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Copy.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Copy.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows the copy of the
    selected files of the source tab in the destination tab. This
    script does not carry out ANY test to know if the destination files
    already exist (it would be enough to change the line using function
    @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE CopyNewer.AmiDisk "Script ARexx CopyNewer.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}CopyNewer.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/CopyNewer.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to recopy the selected files of
    the source tab in the destination tab only if they are more
    recent. The program uses the data posted in the columns dates and hour
    which must naturally be present to allow the correct operation of the
    comparison, if it is not the case an error message is posted. The
    drawers are not treated by this script.

    The execution of script can be stopped while pressing on key ESC or
    while clicking on a button using the function @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK}, whereas
    one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Duplicate.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Duplicate.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Duplicate.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Duplicate.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible
    to duplicate the entries selected in the current source tab. A
    request proposes a file name for the file destination, this name can
    be modified with your suitability. The drawers, like the files,
    can be thus duplicated. The copy is made by using the Copy command of
    DOS (with the options ALL and CLONE).

	The extension added in the name of the files can have passed in
    argument when calling the script (the extension _copy is used by defect).
    Examples:
	CALL("Duplicate", "bis")
	CALL("Duplicate", "bak")

	A test is carried out to know if a file with the name of the file
    created already exists, in this case if the user validates the request
    of confirmation this file would be lost.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditScript.AmiDisk "Script ARexx EditScript.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}EditScript.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/EditScript.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows the edition
    of an existing script. It uses my text editor, Amitex, but it can be
    adapted to any other text editor including/understanding a ARexx port.
    With the launching of script, the program checks initially that Amitex
    is well installed in SYS:Utilities, if this one is not found an error
    message is posted, and script finishes. If all is well a request of
    files allows you to choose a script in the ARexx drawer. This one
    is then loaded in a new window with the editor.

    This script is used by the @{"Macros/Edit script" LINK EditScript} menu.

    Note: this script can be called with an argument, the file passed
    in argument is then automatically loaded by the editor, whatever his
    origin (script, or any text).
    Examples:
	CALL("EditScript","RAM:t/temp")
	CALL("EditScript", FULLNAME(SOURCE, FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)))

    There is another means of calling Amitex: to carry out script
    edit.rexx located in the assigned drawer REXX:. This script makes
    it possible to check that Amitex is or not in memory and to launch it
    only if necessary. That can be done by associating a button to an
    @{"action" LINK Actions} which will carry out the c:rx command :
	RUNCLI("c:rx edit >NIL: <NIL: "+FULLNAME(SOURCE,0),10000,"")
@ENDNODE
@NODE EmptyScript.AmiDisk "Script ARexx EmptyScript.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    This @{"file" LINK ARexx/EmptyScript.AmiDisk/MAIN} does not
    constitute a script to be strictly accurate, but it
    includes the minimal framework advised for a script. It is
    loaded by the text editor Amitex at the time of creation of a
    @{"new script" LINK NewScript}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Filter.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Filter.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Filter.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Filter.AmiDisk/MAIN} is used to filter the
    entries of the current list. A request requires of the user which is
    the filter to be applied then, if the request is validated, the files
    whose name corresponds to the filter are added to the selection.

	The filter is kept in memory for a later use. The command used is
    @{"FILTER" LINK FILTER}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FindString.AmiDisk "Script ARexx FindString.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}FindString.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.03)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/FindString.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible
    to seek a character string in one or more files, and even in drawers.
    When launching the script, a request makes it possible to input the
    character string to be sought, the quotation marks are not allowed
    there. If AWNPipe is installed the request allows, moreover, to define
    additional criteria: research can then distinguish or not the tiny
    ones from the capital letters, research can or not be done in the
    sub-drawers of the selected drawers. Finally it is possible to
    specify the following options of the Search order: QUIET, QUICK, FILE
    and PATTERN. If AWNPipe is not installed research does not distinguish
    the capital letters and the tiny ones and the sub-drawers are not
    traversed and the options are not validated.

    Script tests all the entries which are selected in the source tab
    while using the @{b}Search@{ub} DOS command. The results are posted in a
    window, as they would be in a Shell window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LoadHistory.AmiDisk "ARexx script LoadHistory.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}LoadHistory.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/LoadHistory.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to reload
    a history saved beforehand on disc by using the script
    @{"SaveHistory" LINK SaveHistory.AmiDisk}. The list thus charged is
    available only until the user chose one of his entries. It is then
    the real history of the tab which is found.

    Script can be called without argument (loading in the tab credit
    source) or with two arguments: the first correspondent with the index
    of the tab (from 1 to 10) and the second in the name of the file
    (there is then no request which opens).

    Example :
	CALL("LoadHistory",SOURCE,"Historiques/Onglet"+STR(SOURCE))
	CALL("LoadHistory",DEST,"Historiques/Onglet"+STR(DEST))
    Function STR makes it possible here to create a name corresponding to
    the tab (Tab1 to Tab10).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Makedir.AmiDisk "Script Arexx Makedir.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Makedir.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Makedir.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to create a new drawer. The
    request makes it possible to choose the name of the new drawer,
    moreover if AWNPipe is installed four buttons make it possible to
    create or not an icon, and to enter the new drawer at once that it
    was created or to select it. The selected adjustments will be kept
    in memory as long as the program will run.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MapKey.AmiDisk "Script ARexx MapKey.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}MapKey.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/MapKey.AmiDisk/MAIN} is intended to facilitate the
    input of maco-commands associated with a sequence with keys.
    It is possible to carry out this programming by using the request of
    the preferences (Keys menu), but it often more convenient to carry
    out this operation using this script. When script is launched a first
    request requires of you which is the sequence of key to be programmed,
    you can then seize, either a simple code (has, B, C, etc...), or a key
    of function (F1, f1, F2, etc... F12), either a code
    including one or more special keys (Shift, alt, ctrl, or
    even Shit-Alt or any combination of these three keys, like
    shift-alt-F1 for example, or ctrl-alt-b). Certain special keys can
    also be used:
    -	      - DEL, TAB, UP, DOWN, RIGHT, LEFT, BS, PAGEUP, PAGEDOWN,
	HOME, END and INSERT (their name can be entered in small letters or
    in capital letters) If the sequence of keys is recognized, one second
    request will invite you to input the command to associate this sequence
    keys. If there is already a command associated with this sequence it
    will be integrated automatically into the request, you can then modify
    it or completely change it, with your own way. If you validate this
    request, it will then be enough to press on the keys chosen to carry
    out the associated order.

	@{b}Warning:@{ub} certain keys will not be usable because they are
    associated buttons, and the system intercepts them for its own use
    (these keys are associated no special key, it is thus impossible to use
    them, by against it is possible to use this key with Alt and/or Ctrl).

    Note that this script is runned into asynchronous mode, without
    blocking any tab.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MoveArchive.AmiDisk "Script ARexx MoveArchive.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}MoveArchive.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.05)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/MoveArchive.AmiDisk/MAIN} is very particular,
    I make use of it to backup some files which I downloaded.
    Indeed each downloaded file is accompanied by a info file (I use AWeb,
    who always create this file), and with each time I copy the file, I
    must remove this info file. This script thus makes it possible to copy
    the file, to remove it, then to remove the info file (if it
    exists). For that, it is necessary to select the files to be copied
    (with or without the info files) in the source tab, with the call of
    script the files not comprising info extension are copied in the tab
    destination (if they exist already a request asks you confirmation for
    their replacement), then if very happened well they are removed from
    source tab, as well as the associated info files.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MultiView.AmiDisk "Script ARexx MultiView.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}MultiView.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/MultiView.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to launch MultiView for each file selected
    in the active tab, on the source side. If a drawer is selected
    MultiView will open an asl requester to select a file in it.

    The script can be called with no argument (all selected entries
    of the active source tab are displayed), or with three arguments :
	CALL("MultiView",SOURCE,DEST,N)
	The third argument (N) is used to select an entry to be
	used by MultiView, even it's not selected.
	The second argument (DEST) is not used, it's only placed here
	for compatibility with other scripts calls.
	If argument N is null, the first selected entry only will
	be displayed.

    Note : call of MultiView is asynchronous, so all selected
    entries are launched at the same time, if many entries are
    selected, you'll get a strange behaviour... perhaps a crash
    if memory is low.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NewScript.AmiDisk "Script ARexx NewScript.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}NewScript.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/NewScript.AmiDisk/MAIN} is intended to facilitate the
    writing of new scripts, it allows to create of a script by
    integrating the preliminary minimal framework of this script
    (by loading the ARexx/EmptyScript.AmiDisk file). It uses my text
    editor Amitex, but it can be adapted to any other text editor
    integrating a ARexx port. With the launching of script, the program
    checks initially that Amitex is well installed in SYS:Utilities, if
    this one is not found an error message is posted, and script finishes.
    If the program is well installed, script edit.rexx is then carried
    out. This script makes it possible to test if Amitex runs already, if
    it is the case the program will not be started again but a new window
    is simply open. A request then makes it possible to enter the name of
    this script (with the AmiDisk extension). The window is then
    re-elected with this name, and some information (error messages,
    heading in particular) is updated automatically. Lastly, the cursor is
    placed where the new script instructions must be written.

    This script is used by the menu @{"Macros/New script" LINK NewScript}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ReadASCII.AmiDisk "Script ARexx ReadASCII.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ReadASCII.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/ReadASCII.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows the reading
    in ASCII of the specified files. It can be called in two ways:

    - with 3 arguments: CALL ("ReadASCII", source_tab, destination, entry)
    Then only the specified file is then read (the argument
    destination is not used). If the number of entry is null, only the
    first selected entry is read.

    - without any argument, it then allows the treatment of all the
    entries selected in the current tab. If the reading is cancelled the
    following files will not be read.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ReadFiles.AmiDisk "Script ARexx ReadFiles.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ReadFiles.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/ReadFiles.AmiDisk/MAIN} manages the most suitable posting
    for each type of files: it calls function READASC for
    the files of the ASCII type and function READHEX for
    the binary files.

    It can be called in two ways:

    - with 3 arguments: CALL ("ReadFiles", source, destination, entry)
    Then only the specified file is then read (the argument
    destination is not used). If the number of entry is null, only the
    first selected entry is read.

    - without any argument, it then allows the treatment of all the
    entries selected in the running tab, the ones after the others. If
    the reading is cancelled the following files will not be read.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ReadHexa.AmiDisk "Script ARexx ReadHexa.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ReadHexa.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/ReadHexa.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows the reading into hexadecimal
    of the specified files. It can be called in two ways:

    - with 3 arguments: CALL ("ReadHexa", source, destination, entry)
    Then only the specified file is then read (the argument
    destination is not used). If the number of entry is null, only the
    first selected entry is read.

    - without any argument, it then allows the treatment of all the
    entries selected in the current tab. If the reading is cancelled the
    following files will not be read.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Rename.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Rename.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Rename.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Rename.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to rename
    one or more entries of a list. It can be called in two ways:

    - with three arguments: CALL ("Rename", source, destination, entry)
    If the number of the source tab is null it is the selected tab
    at the time of the call of the script which will be treated. The
    number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null, only the first selected entry will be treated. The
    argument destination is not used. A request is opened, it comprises
    the name of the file, the user can modify it, if the request is
    validated the file will be renamed.

    - without any argument (treatment of all the entries selected in
    the running tab). If several entries are selected, the requests will
    be open the ones after the others. If one of these requests is
    cancelled the treatment will be stopped.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Root.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Root.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Root.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Root.AmiDisk/MAIN} ensures the reading of
    the root directory of the specified tab or the current tab if it
    is called without argument. The determination of the root directory is
    made simply by keeping path corresponding to the tab only what
    precedes the two points (:).
@ENDNODE
@NODE RunWB.AmiDisk "Script ARexx RunWB.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}RunWB.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/RunWB.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to
    launch a command as if it had been launched from Workbench. If it is
    called without argument, it treats all the entries which are selected
    in the active source tab. If no entry is active the window of the
    drawer associated with the tab is open on Workbench. If the
    entries are drawers those are open on Workbench, if they are
    executables ones they are launched, if not there is an error message.

    If the call of script is made with three arguments, only the specified
    entry will be treated.
    Example: CALL("RunWB", SOURCE, DEST, FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))
    This script uses the @{"RUNWB" LINK RUNWB} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SaveHistory.AmiDisk "Script ARexx SaveHistory.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SaveHistory.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/SaveHistory.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible
    to save the history of the credit source tab on disc, in order to
    reload it later on. A request makes it possible to choose the file of
    destination. During the time of activity of script, the list of the
    tab is replaced by that of the history, if necessary. It restores its
    initial contents after saving.

    Script can be called without argument (saving of the credit tab
    source) or with two arguments: the first correspondent with the index
    of the tab (from 1 to 10) and the second in the name of the file
    (there is then no request which opens).
    Example of call:
	CALL("SaveHistory",DEST, "Histories/Tab"+STR(DEST))
    Function STR makes it possible here to create a name corresponding to the
    tabs (Tab1 to Tab10).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Search.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Search.AmiDisk"

    @{b}Search.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.03)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Search.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to
    seek a file by specifying whole or part of its name, by using wildcards
    (# *, etc) if you want it. Research is carried out on the entries of
    the source tab which is active at the time of the call of script. If
    a file corresponding to the name given in the box of request is found,
    the repertory where it was found is open in the source tab. The
    required string is memorized, also it will be recalled for edition
    to the following call of script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SelectedSize.AmiDisk "Script ARexx SelectedSize.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SelectedSize.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/SelectedSize.AmiDisk/MAIN} calculates the
    total size of the files which are selected in the current list. It
    uses for that the CalcSize.AmiDisk script, which allows itself to
    return the value associated with the chain defining the size with a
    file. The calculated size is posted in a request.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Startup.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Startup.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Startup.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.00)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Startup.AmiDisk/MAIN} contains @{"definitions" LINK DEF} of functions which
    can then be used in other scripts or macros-orders, in order to
    simplify their writing.
    You can naturally incorporate in it all the definitions which seem
    useful to you.
    Some @{"variables" LINK Variable} are also initialized there.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ToLeft.AmiDisk "Script ARexx ToLeft.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ToLeft.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/ToRight.AmiDisk/MAIN} recopy contents of
    the list of the active tab of tight in that of left-hand side. The
    order of sorting of the right tab is recopied in that of left-hand
    side.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ToRight.AmiDisk "Script ARexx ToRight.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ToRight.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/ToRight.AmiDisk/MAIN} recopy contents of
    the list of the active tab of left in that of right-hand side. The
    order of sorting of the left tab is recopied in that of right-hand
    side.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Touch.AmiDisk "Script ARexx Touch.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Touch.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.02)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/Touch.AmiDisk/MAIN} makes it possible to
    fix the date of one or more files at the current date and hour. It
    treats all the selected entries of the current list when it is called
    without argument. If it is called with three arguments, only the
    specified entry will be treated, for example
	CALL("Touch", SOURCE, 0, FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))
	will treat only the first selected entry (the second
	argument is ignored). The same result would be also
	obtained with this writing:
	CALL("Touch", SOURCE, 0, 0)

    It uses the Touch command, this one must of course be installed
    beforehand in C: (available on OS4depot).

    It can be used for a programmable @{"menu" LINK Macro...}.
    Use: CALL("Touch")

    The execution of the script can be stopped while pressing on key
    ESC or while clicking on a button using the function @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK},
    whereas one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UnFilter.AmiDisk "Script ARexx UnFilter.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}UnFilter.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/UnFilter.AmiDisk/MAIN} is used to filter
    the entries of the current list. A request requires of the user which
    is the filter to be applied then, if the request is validated, the
    files whose name corresponds to the filter are unselected, if
    needed.

    The filter string is kept in memory for a later use.
    The function used is @{"UNFILTER" LINK UNFILTER}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UnProtect.AmiDisk "Script ARexx UnProtect.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}UnProtect.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/UnProtect.AmiDisk/MAIN} is used to position
    bits RWED of the files objects of the command. It is useful after the
    decompression of certain files resulting from the Unix world or which
    decompressed by buggy software which does not position these bits
    correctly. It can be called in two ways:

    - with 3 arguments: CALL ("UnProtect", source, destination, entry)
    If the number of the source tab is null it is the selected tab
    at the time of the call of the script which will be used. The number
    of the entry owes of course being ranging between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.
    Examples:
	CALL("UNPROTECT", 0, 0, 5)
	CALL("UNPROTECT", SOURCE, 0, FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))

    - without any argument (treatment of all the entries
    selected in the running tab).
    Example: CALL("UnProtect").
    This form can be used for a programmable @{"menu" LINK Macro...}.

    This script uses the command c:Protect. The treatment of the
    drawers is made with option ALL, i.e. that all the files and
    drawers which are included there will be treated.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UpdateCopy.AmiDisk "Script ARexx UpdateCopy.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}UpdateCopy.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.04)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/UpdateCopy.AmiDisk/MAIN} can be used to
    ensure the conditional copy of drawers and/or files, by using the
    UpdateCopy command, the latter is available on Aminet. It allows the
    copy of files whose creation date more recent, is compared with that
    of the file destination, if there already exists. If the file
    destination does not exist, the copy takes place naturally.

    Script calls the command with option ALL for the drawers.

    Script can be called in two ways:

    - with three arguments: CALL ("UpdateCopy", source, destination, entry)
    If the number of the source tab is null
    it is the selected tab at the time of the call of the script
    which will be used. The number of the destination tab must
    imperatively be specified (normally equal to @{"DEST" LINK DEST}). The
    number of entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.
    Examples:	CALL("UPDATECOPY", 0, DEST, 5)
		CALL("UPDATECOPY", SOURCE, DEST, FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))

    - without any argument (copy of all the entries selected
    since the running source tab in the destination tab).
    Example: CALL("UpdateCopy").
    This form can be used for a programmable @{"menu" LINK Macro...}.

    Note: the UpdateCopy command has, in my opinion, a defect:
    the copied file has not the same date and hour of creation that of
    origin but those of the moment of the copy, an option CLONE would
    have been here welcome...

    The execution of script can be stopped while pressing on key
    ESC or while clicking on a button using the function @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK},
    whereas one at least of the two tabs is active.
@ENDNODE
@NODE WBInfo.AmiDisk "Script ARexx WBInfo.AmiDisk"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}WBInfo.AmiDisk@{ub} (Version 1.01)

    This @{"script" LINK ARexx/WBInfo.AmiDisk/MAIN} allows the opening of
    the request of information of Workbench for the desired entries. It
    can be called in two ways:

    - with three arguments: CALL ("WBInfo", source, destination, entry)
    If the number of source is 0 it is the selected source tab
    at the time of the call of the script which will be used. If the
    number of entry is null information the path related to the specified
    tab will concern.

    - without any argument (treatment of all the entries selected in
    the running tab). If several entries are selected, the requests will
    be open the ones after the others, but it is impossible to cease the
    operation, even if you click on "Cancel" in the request of
    information, because Workbench alas does not return any particular
    value in this case. If no entry is selected information the way
    related to the current tab will concern. This form can be used for a
    programmable @{"menu" LINK Macro...} or a button.
@ENDNODE
