@NODE DEF "ARexx Function DEF"
@TOC Fonctions

    You can define an unspecified number of functions using of the
    internal functions like any operator. One of these functions can even
    call upon another function previously defined. The arguments can be
    of an unspecified type, it must simply correspond to the types awaited
    by the functions which will be called or being compatible with the
    operators used.

    There cannot be more than one declaration in the same line.

    The form of these definitions is following form:
    @{B}DEF function_name(argument,...) = @{I}definition of functions@{UI}@{UB}

    Keyword @{B}DEF@{UB} must @{B}begin@{UB} the definition, without any preliminary
    space.

    The name of the functions can include from 1 to 13
    alphanumerics, including the accentuated letters and the underlining
    (_). The first character must however always be a letter. The internal
    functions cannot be redefined. The number of the arguments is limited
    to 15 to the maximum. This number is fixed for a given definition (you
    cannot declare function having a variable number of arguments). There
    must be at least an argument in the definition, but this one can not
    be used. The arguments must of course have distinct names.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    DEF GETROOT(TAB) IF(POS(":",CURRDIR(TAB))>0,GETDIR(TAB,SUBS(CURRDIR(TAB),1,POS(":",CURRDIR(TAB)))),MESSAGE("Path undefined"+CHR(10)+"Operation not possible"))
    DEF ISDIR(TAB,N)=IF(GETCLASS(FULLNAME(TAB,N))=="[DRAWER]",1,0)
    or (better because string [DRAWER] could be modified by user in the prefs)
    DEF ISDIR(TAB,N)=IF(DESCRIPT(FULLNAME(TAB,N))=="directory",1,0)
    The call of the function will be then made as for any other function:
    GETROOT(SOURCE) for example.
    IF(ISDIR(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),MESSAGE("It's a drawer that is selected"),MESSAGE("It's a file that is selected"))

    The redefinition of a function having already been defined is
    possible, the new definition replaces the old one then. This can be
    useful when you try to define a complex function, it can then be
    necessary to carry out several tests before obtaining the good result.

    The functions thus defined are available for all the tasks launched in
    the same session, they remain memorized even when the task which
    determined it stops. They are managed by the principal process.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"READDEF" LINK READDEF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ABS "ARexx Function ABS"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}ABS(number)@{UB}

    This function returns the absolute value of a number given in
    argument. This number can be in a @{"variable" LINK Variable}.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    ABS(-8)     return 8
    ABS(4)      return 4
    ABS(N)      return the absolute value of the number that is
		present in variable N

    @{I}Note :@{UI} numbers must be integers, variables must
    naturelly be of numeric type (not a string).
@ENDNODE
@NODE ACTION "ARexx Function ACTION"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ACTION (tab, entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to launch the first action associated
    with an entry, if there are some, as if the user had carried out there
    a double click (depend on the class to which the entry belongs).
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the active tab which is used. The number of the entry must lie
    between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null the first
    selected entry will be treated.

    Caution: certain commands use the destination tab, this one
    corresponds to this tab at the time of the call of the function,
    even if the specified tab in argument is same side...

    Function @{"ENTRY" LINK ENTRY} takes the value of the entry that has
    been specified by this command, so you it can't be used to pass
    an entry, use FIRSTSEL(SOURCE) or 0 to pass the first selected
    entry index.

    The returned value is 0 if there no error occured.

    See also : @{"GETCLASS" LINK GETCLASS}, @{"REQACT" LINK REQACT}, @{"DOACTION" LINK DOACTION}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ADDENTRY "ARexx Function ADDENTRY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ADDENTRY(tab,tiroir,"nom","taille","bits","date","heure","commentaire")@{ub}

    This command makes it possible to add an element to the list
    corresponding to the specified tab. The number of the tab must lie
    between 1 and 10. The second parameter (drawer) must be to 1 if it
    acts of an entry corresponding to a drawer (the corresponding cell
    will be added in front of the name), to 0 if it acts of a file. The
    name must imperatively be a nonnull character string. The validity of
    this name is not checked. The other parameters can be null chains
    (""), however if the date (or the hour) is specified the hour (or
    date) must also be it. The format must correspond to the format
    chosen in the preferences. The bits of protection (the fifth argument)
    must, if they are specified, correspond to the chain HSPARWED, in
    which each character can be replaced by an indent (-).

    The returned value is 0 if very happened well. Another value
    indicates that the operation could not be carried out (report lack for
    example). The new entry is normally classified in the list by holding
    account of current @{"sorting" LINK SortButton}.

    If the name passed in argument already exists in the list, the
    existing entry will be replaced by that which passed to the function,
    the various parameters each one being replaced by the new last ones in
    argument (size, bits, etc...).

    WARNING: no checking is made when with the validity of the
    parameters compared to what is pointed by the list. You can in
    particular add a repertory or file name whereas this one does not
    exist in the drawer pointed in the tab...

    See also : @{"REMENTRY" LINK REMENTRY}, @{"NEWENTRY" LINK NEWENTRY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ADDICON "ARexx Function ADDICON"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ADDICON(tab,entry)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the active tab which is used. This command allows the addition of an
    icon one or more entries of the specified tab. The selected icon
    depends on @{"class" LINK Classes} of the file concerned, like defined
    in the preferences.

    The parameter corresponding to the entry can take the following
    values:
    - if it is a negative number, all the entries of the tab
    will be treated, that they are or not selected.
    - if this number is null, only the selected entries will be treated.
    - if it is a positive number, only the corresponding entry will be
    treated. The number of the entry must then lie between 1 and
    @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    Caution: if an icon exists already the command will be stopped (Posting
    of an error message : The icon already exists).

    The function returns the number of icons which could be added without
    error (version 2.00).
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASC "ARexx Function ASC"
@TOC Fonctions

    @{B}ASC("text",row)@{UB}

    This function returns the ASCII code of the character pertaining to
    the chain of text passed in argument, of the specified row. The row
    must lie between 1 and the length of the chain passed in argument.

    @{I}Examples:@{UI}
	ASC("essai", 1) returns 101 (ASCII code of the e character)
	ASC(TEXT, LEN(TEXT)) returns the ASCII code of the last
	    character of @{"variable" LINK Variable} TEXT.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"CHR" LINK CHR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASSIGNS "ARexx Function ASSIGNS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ASSIGNS(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the list of the assignments
    in a tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is
    null it is the source running tab which will be used.

    If you want that the tab to be displayed at once use function
    @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY}; if not this posting will take place at the
    end of the task.

    The function returns the number of entries which were read (Version 2.00).

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"DEVICES" LINK DEVICES}, @{"VOLUMES" LINK VOLUMES}, @{"HISTORY" LINK HISTORY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE BREAK "ARexx Function BREAK"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}BREAK(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to ask for the interruption of a
    treatment in a tab. Attention, this request cannot always be taken
    into account, for example if a task of the Workbench type were
    launched it could not be stopped, but if several entries were selected
    at the time of the call of this function, the entries which were not
    treated yet will not be.

    This function was defined to be used with a button, associated an
    internal command as BREAK(SOURCE) the same effect can be obtained
    while pressing on the Esc key when the source tab is active.

    See also : @{"CHECKESC" LINK CHECKESC}, @{"EXIT" LINK EXIT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE BUBBLES "ARexx Function BUBBLES"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}BUBBLES(-1/0/1)@{ub}

    This function is used to toggle using bubble help in the main
    window. The preferences requesters can't take the result of
    this function if they are already open, this flag is taken in
    account only while they are opening their window.
    If the argument is 0, bubbles are inhibit, if it is positive
    bubbles are activated, if it is negative the function has no effect.

    The returned value is always the state of the function before its
    activation.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CALCSIZE "ARexx Function CALCSIZE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}CALCSIZE(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function allows to calculate the size associated with an entry.
    It is useful in particular to determine the size of the drawers,
    this one is not calculated automatically with the reading of the
    drawers, because this operation can be relatively long.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null
    only the selected entries are treated, if it is equal to -1 all the
    entries are treated.

    Example of command:
    IF(FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)>0,CALCSIZE(SOURCE,0),CALCSIZE(SOURCE,-1)):IF((SORT(SOURCE,-1)==1)|(SORT(SOURCE,-1)==4),SORT(SOURCE,SORT(SOURCE,-1)),0)

    This command makes it possible to launch the function either for
    the entries selected only, if there is, or for all the entries if
    there is no selection in progress. If the sorting in force in this
    tab holds account of the size of the entries, the sorting is
    done again to hold account of the results.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CALL "ARexx Function CALL"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}CALL("script", argument1, argument2...)@{UB}

    Call of an ARexx script. The name of the @{"script" LINK Script}, given in
    argument, does not have to include the extension "AmiDisk". This
    function is not useful in an ARexx script but can be useful in a
    @{"macro-command" LINK Direct} (ALT-Fx or local macro). The call can be
    made while specifying from 0 to 15 arguments (@{"numeric" LINK Nombres} or
    @{"strings of chars" LINK Strings}).

    The execution of the script is made into asynchronous, i.e. that the hand
    is returned to the calling program before the end of the execution
    of script. The returned value is the name of script (without much
    interest)...

    Note that the execution of this function involves the automatic
    creation of the ARexx port associated with the task which carries out
    the macro one. This port is destroyed as soon as the task finishes.
    There can be several tasks which turn simultaneously, with each one
    their respective port.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
	'CALL("EditScript","NewScript.AmiDisk")'
	'CALL("multiplier",1.5,X)'
@ENDNODE
@NODE CHECKESC "ARexx Function CHECKESC"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}CHECKESC(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know if key ESC were in a hurry
    whereas the specified tab was active. It thus allows the
    interruption of an ARexx script, when such a script carries out a loop
    to treat several selected entries for example. The returned value is
    null only if key ESC was not pressed.

    @{i}Example :@{ui}
	'SOURCE'
	tab=result
	...
	'CHECKESC('tab')'
	if result~=0 then exit

    See also : @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK}
@ENDNODE

@NODE CHR "ARexx Function CHR"
@TOC Fonctions

    @{B}CHR(code)@{UB}

    Return the character having the specified ASCII code.

    Used to obtain a jump of line (CHR(10)) or a special character
    nonpresent on the keyboard. The code can vary from 1 to 255 maximum.

    You can add one of these characters (or any other to a character
    string with a writing of the following form :
	"String "+CHR(0xF5)

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"ASC" LINK ASC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLOSEBAR "ARexx function CLOSEBAR"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}CLOSEBAR("toolbar")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to close the toolbar whose name
    passed in argument. The name must include the complete path, such as it
    was used at the time of the loading of the bar. If the bar were not
    charged an error will be posted (Incorrect argument).

    See also : @{"LOADBAR" LINK LOADBAR}, @{"EDITBAR" LINK EDITBAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CMP "ARexx function CMP"
@TOC Files

    @{b}CMP ("file1", "file2")@{ub}

    This function compares the contents of two files.
    It returns 0 if the two files have the same content, else it
    returns the offset of the first different byte (1 for the first
    byte...)

    The two files must exists, or an error will occur. If a drawer
    is passed an error will also occur (Argument type mismatch).

    See also : @{"CmpFiles" LINK CmpFiles.AmiDisk} script
@ENDNODE
@NODE COLSIZE "ARexx function COLSIZE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}COLSIZE(tab,column)@{ub}

    This function returns the width of a given column in
    a tab. If the value is null or negative, the column
    is hidden.
    The tab number have to be set between 1 and 10 (or 0
    for the current source tab).
    The column number have to be set between 0 and 5,
    0 is for names, 1 for size, 2 for bits, 3 for date,
    4 for time, 5 for the comment.
@ENDNODE
@NODE COLUMNS "ARexx function COLUMNS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}COLUMNS(tab,names,size,bits,date,time,comment)@{ub}

    This function allows to define the width of each column of a
    given list. If a value is null or negative the column is not
    displayed.
    The tab number have to be set between 1 and 10 (or 0
    for the current source tab).
    The names column can't be hidden (negative or null values
    not allowed).

    It is very simple to create macro making it possible to rock the
    posting of a given column, thus for the Bits column :
    COLUMNS(SOURCE,COLSIZE(SOURCE,0),COLSIZE(SOURCE,1),-COLSIZE(SOURCE,2),COLSIZE(SOURCE,3),COLSIZE(SOURCE,4),COLSIZE(SOURCE,5))
    If this macro is associated a button, the support on this button will
    make it possible to post or hide the Bits column, according to whether
    it were or not masked.

    See also : @{"REQCOLS" LINK REQCOLS}, @{"COLSIZE" LINK COLSIZE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE COMMENT "ARexx Function COMMENT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}COMMENT(tab,entry,"Comment")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to associate a comment a file or
    drawer (or with several).
    The number of the tab must lie betweens 1 and 10, if it is null
    the current source tab is used.

    The parameter corresponding to the entry can take the following
    values:
    - if it is a negative number, all the entries of the tab
    will be treated, that they are or not selected.
    - if this number is null, only the selected entries will be treated.
    - if it is a positive number, only the corresponding entry will be
    treated. The number of the entry must then lie between 1 and
    @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    See also : @{"GETCOMM" LINK GETCOMM}, @{"SETCOMM" LINK SETCOMM}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONTENT "ARexx Function CONTENT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}content = CONTENT(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know what is in a list.
    The number of the tab must lie betweens 1 and 10, if it is null
    the current source tab is used.
    The returned string can be :
	- EMPTY if the list is empty
	- History list
	- Volumes list
	- Assigns list
	- Devices list
	- DIR if the list is a drawer

    Examples : see scripts @{"ToLeft" LINK ToLeft.AmiDisk}, @{"ToRight" LINK ToRight.AmiDisk}, @{"SaveHistory" LINK SaveHistory.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE COPY "ARexx Function COPY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}COPY (source, destination, entry)@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to copy the specified entries from
    the source tab to the destination tab. Files and drawers can be
    copied using this function.
    The tabs can be specified using the @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE} and @{"DEST" LINK DEST} functions, but
    you can use any tab, between 1 and 10. The source tab can be null,
    in this case the current source tab will be used.

    The entry can take the next values :
     - if it is a negative number, all the entries of the source
     tab will be copied, either they are selected or not.
     - if this number is null, only the selected entries will be
     copied.
     - if this number is positive, only the specified entry will
     be copied. The entry number can be included between 1 and
     @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    The function returns the number of entries that were copied.

    The intervention of an unspecified error stops the execution of macro
    normally. There is a warning message if a file is already existing and
    that it is thus replaced by another provided that @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay}
    were suitably fixed, or although function REQOVER returns 1.

    The ordering of copy can be stopped by pressing key ESC if one of the
    source or destination tabs is selected. It is also possible to use a
    button using order @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK} to stop this function.

    Examples :
	COPY(SOURCE,DEST,0)     "classical" command
	COPY(1,2,-1)            copy all entries from tab 1 in tab 2.

    Note : the command can be successfull only if the TWO tabs are free
    when the fonction is called.

    See also : @{"MOVE" LINK MOVE}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CURRDEST "ARexx Function CURRDEST"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}CURRDEST@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the destination tab AT THE TIME
    of the CALL of the function. For information, the tabs are numbered
    from 1 to 10, on the basis of the left towards the line.

    This value can change after the launching of a function, if a script
    carries out for example copies of files, the user can change the active
    before the script did not finish its task, the tab of destination can
    have changed very well.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE}, @{"CURRSRC" LINK CURRSRC}, @{"STATUS" LINK STATUS}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CURRDIR "ARexx Function CURRDIR"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}CURRDIR(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the path associated with a
    tab. If the tab contains a list of volumes, assignments, devices
    or the history, the returned chain will be null (""). The number of
    thetab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the current source
    tab is used.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CURRSRC "ARexx Function CURRSRC"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}CURRSRC@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the source tab AT THE TIME of
    the CALL of the function. For information, the tabs are numbered
    from 1 to 10, on the basis of the left towards the line.

    This value can change after the launching of a task, if a script
    carries out for example copies of files, the user can change the
    active tab before script did not finish its task, the destination
    tab can have changed very well. If script uses the function SOURCE,
    this index will keep the value which it had taken at the beginning
    of script, function CURRSRC makes it possible to know if this
    tab changed.

    The use of this function does not block the tab.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE}, @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, @{"CURRDEST" LINK CURRDEST}, @{"STATUS" LINK STATUS}

    Examples of use : scripts @{"Filter" LINK Filter.AmiDisk}, @{"UnFilter" LINK UnFilter.AmiDisk}, @{"FindString" LINK FindString.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DATATYPE "ARexx Function DATATYPE"
@TOC Files

    @{b}DATATYPE ("filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the type returned by DataTypes
    for the specified file.

    A textual file returns the ASCII string normally, an image IFF returns
    IFF, executable returns the string Binary, etc...

    See also : @{"ISASCII" LINK ISASCII}, @{"DESCRIPT" LINK DESCRIPT}, @{"DATGROUP" LINK DATGROUP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DATE" "ARexx Function DATE"
@TOC "Divers"

    @{b}DATE(day)@{ub}

	Return the current date. If the argument day is different
    from zero, the day of the week is included. The format used
    depends on the adjustment carried out in @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay} for
    the format of the date.


	@{i}Examples :@{ui}
	    DATE(0)     return 26-Dec-96
	    DATE(1)     return Thursday 26-Dec-96

	@{i}See also :@{ui} @{"DAYS" LINK "DAYS"}, @{"TIME" LINK "TIME"}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DATGROUP "ARexx Function DATGROUP"
@TOC Files

    @{b}DATGROUP ("filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the group returned by
    DataTypes for the specified file.

    A textual file returns normally the string Text, an image returns
    the string Picture, executable returns the string System, etc...


    See also : @{"ISASCII" LINK ISASCII}, @{"DESCRIPT" LINK DESCRIPT}, @{"DATATYPE" LINK DATATYPE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "DAYS" "ARexx Function DAYS"
@TOC "Divers"

    @{b}DAYS(date1,date2)@{ub}

	Return the number of days separating the two dates.
	If the first date is former to the second the returned value is positive
	if not it is negative (or null if the two dates agree).
	The format of the date must correspond to that obtained by instruction
	@{"DATE(0)" LINK "DATE"}, i.e. that the day of the week should not be
	included. However you can specify one day of the week, but then
	without the date, thus DAYS ("Wednesday", "18-Sep-95") returns the
	number of days separating last Wednesday last from September 18 95.
	You can also specify "yesterday" or "today". To note that the dates
	must be posterior at January 1 78. Thus the following date 20-Oct-14,
	corresponds to October 20 of the year 2014.

	Warning :  this function does not turn over an error provided that
	the dates passed in argument are with the format defined in
	@{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay} for the format of the date.

	@{i}See also :@{ui} @{"TIME" LINK "TIME"}.

	Example of use : script @{"CopyNewer" LINK CopyNewer.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DBLCLICK "ARexx Function DBLCLICK"
@TOC Interactivitť

      @{b}DBLCLICK (-1/0/1)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to determine the behavior of the
    program when the user carries out a double click on an entry in a
    list. If the argument is null, the double clicks are not taken
    into account, if it is equal to 1, they are it (the first action
    associated with the selected object will be launched). If the argument
    is equal to -1 no change is made.

    The returned value is the value in force BEFORE the execution of the
    function. The initial state depends on the adjustment made in
    @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay}.

    This function was written to be associated a button of the bistable
    type. The function making it possible to initialize the button is then
    the following one: DBLCLICK(-1) the command making it possible to
    toggle the state of the function is form: DBLCLICK(DBLCLICK(-1)?1)
    Explanation of operation: the operator ? carry out an exclusive OR.
    DBLCLICK(-1) returns the state of the function (0 or 1), this result
    XOR 1 reverses the result, which passed by again with the function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DELETE "ARexx Function DELETE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}DELETE(tab,entry)@{UB}

    Remove the entries of the specified tab. The files and the drawers
    associated with these entries of course are also removed. The number
    of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is the tab
    source running which is used.

    The parameter corresponding to the entry can take the following
    values:
    - if it is a negative number, all the entries of the tab
    source will be removed, that they are or not selected.
    - if this number is null, only the selected entries will be removed.
    - if it is a positive number, only the eniŤme entry will be removed.
    The number of the entry must then lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    The intervention of an unspecified error stops the execution of macro
    normally. There is no warning message before the suppression of the
    files and/or repertories.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DESCRIPT "ARexx Function DESCRIPT"
@TOC Files

    @{b}DESCRIPT ("filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the description returned by
    DataTypes for the specified file.

    A repertory returns the chain "directory". A textual file returns the
    chain normally corresponding to its type (C-Source for example,
    ASCII...), an image IFF returns chain ILBM, executable returns the
    chain binary, etc...

    See also : @{"ISASCII" LINK ISASCII}, @{"DATATYPE" LINK DATATYPE}, @{"DATGROUP" LINK DATGROUP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DEST "ARexx Function DEST"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}DEST@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the destination tab. For
    information, the tabs are numbered from 1 to 10, on the basis of the
    left towards the line.

    When a script is launched, this value remains constant, even if the
    user changes active tab before script does not finish. Use function
    CURRDEST if you want to know the number of the destination tab at a
    given moment.

    To know if the tab is free or not, use function @{"STATUS" LINK STATUS}.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"CURRDEST" LINK CURRDEST}, @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE}, @{"CURRSRC" LINK CURRSRC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DEVICES "ARexx Function DEVICES"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}DEVICES(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the list of the devices in a
    tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null
    it is the source tab running which will be used.

    If you want that the tab is displayed at once use function
    @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY}; if not this posting will take place at the
    end of the task.

    The function returns the number of entries which were read (Version
    2.00).

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"ASSIGNS" LINK ASSIGNS}, @{"VOLUMES" LINK VOLUMES}, @{"HISTORY" LINK HISTORY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DISKPATH "ARexx Function DISKPATH"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}DISKPATH@{ub}

    This function returns the path of the drawer since which AmiDisk was
    launched. This way always includes ':' or one '/' final.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DISPLAY "ARexx Function DISPLAY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}DISPLAY(tab)@{ub}

    This function allows to display the specified list. It is often used
    in scripts to announce for example that a tab is busy, indeed
    when a script is launched, the posting of the source tab (and
    destination) is not inevitably updated automatically, to avoid the
    flickerings of posting. If an error message or a request must be
    carried out at a given time it can be interesting for showing
    well to the user that the tab is blocked.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    current source tab is used.

    Return the state of the Fast Display flag (null result if flag not
    marked, different from 0 if not).

    See also : @{"REFRESH" LINK REFRESH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DOACTION "ARexx Function DOACTION"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}DOACTION (tab, entry, "action")@{ub}

    This function allows to execute an action, defined in
    @{"preferences" LINK Actions}.
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    current source tab is used.
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it's 0 the first selected entry is used.
    The name of the action must match a defined action as they
    have been defined in preferences (lower or uppercase).
    The function @{"ENTRY" LINK ENTRY} take the value of the entry that
    has been specified by the command.

    The returned value is 0 if there no were error.

    See also : @{""ACTION" LINK ACTION}, @{"REQACT" LINK REQACT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE EDITBAR "ARexx Function EDITBAR"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}EDITBAR("toolbar")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to edit the toolbar whose name
    passed in argument. The name must include the complete path, such as it
    was used at the time of the loading of the bar. If the bar were not
    loaded an error will be posted (Incorrect argument).

    The returned value is -1 if edition was cancelled, if the user
    validate the edition, 0 is returned if the bar could be open
    else a positive value is returned (error code).

    See also : @{"LOADBAR" LINK LOADBAR}, @{"CLOSEBAR" LINK CLOSEBAR}, @{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ENTRIES "ARexx Function ENTRIES"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ENTRIES(tab)@{ub}

    This command returns the number of entries of the tab specified in
    argument. This number includes the drawers and the files. The
    number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    current tab source is used.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ENTRY "ARexx Function ENTRY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}ENTRY@{ub}

    This function must be used by commands associated to
    @{"actions" LINK Actions}. It returns the index of the entry that have to
    be treated. It's set to the first selected entry when a new
    task is launched, but some functions can also set it :
    @{"DOACTION" LINK DOACTION}, @{"ACTION" LINK ACTION}...
@ENDNODE
@NODE EXEC "ARexx Function EXEC"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}EXEC("string")@{UB}

    Ask the interpretation and the execution of the character string
    passed in argument, as if it acted of a line of order. The result
    depends naturally on the contents of the chain passed in argument.

    @{I}Example:@{UI}
	EXEC(READMAP("CTRL -)") carries out the sequence associated
				with the combination with keys CTRL-)
	EXEC(READMAP("F5"))     carries out the sequence associated
				with the F5 key.

    An interesting function can be defined by using an instruction DEF:
	DEF EXECKEY(X)=EXEC(READMAP(X))
	it then becomes possible to write :
	    EXECKEY("F5")
	    ou
	    EXECKEY("Alt-F5")
@ENDNODE
@NODE EXIT "ARexx Function EXIT"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}EXIT@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to close the program (similar to a
    click on the button of closing of the principal window or to a
    selection of small Projet/Quitter). If one or more tasks are running,
    the operation will fail.

    See also : @{"BREAK" LINK BREAK}, @{"CHECKESC" LINK CHECKESC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FILEPART "ARexx Function FILEPART"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}FILEPART("name")@{UB}

    This function returns a file name, without the complete path.

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    FILEPART("RAM:sources/file")    return†file.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"PATHPART" LINK PATHPART}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FILTER "ARexx Function FILTER"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}FILTER(tab,"pattern")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to filter the entries of a tab.
    The number of the tab must be between 1 and 10, if it's 0 the
    active source tab will be used. The files corresponding
    to the pattern are selected. The pattern can include all the
    generic characters used by AmigaDOS (#?*[])...

    The function returns the number of entries corresponding to the
    search criterion which were found, that they are beforehand marked
    or not.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	FILTER(SOURCE,"*.c")
	FILTER(DEST,"*.[cho]")

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"UNFILTER" LINK UNFILTER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FIND "ARexx Function FIND"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}FIND(tab,entry,"filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to seek a file or a drawer starting
    from the tab and of the specified entry, this one must of course be
    a drawer so that research can succeed.
    The complete name of the file (or drawer) that was found is returned
    by the function, if it succeeds, an empty string is returned in other
    cases.
    The file name can be given by including generic characters (*@?[]).

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it's 0
    the current source tab is used.
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it's 0 the first selected entry is used.

    Example :
	FIND(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE),"*.c")

    See also : ARexx script @{"Search" LINK Search.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FIRSTSEL "ARexx Function FIRSTSEL"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}FIRSTSEL(tab)@{UB}

    This function returns the number of the first selected entry. If no
    object is marked the returned value is null.
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it's 0 the
    current source tab is used.

    An ARexx script having to parse all the selected entries could have
    the following structure:
	'SOURCE'; source=result
	'ENTRIES('source')'; total=result
	'FIRSTSEL('source')'; n=result
	if n<1 then exit
	do while n <= total
	    'TEST('source','n')'
	    if result=1 then do
		... parsing the entry...
	    end
	    n=n+1
	end

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, @{"MARK" LINK MARK}, @{"UNMARK" LINK UNMARK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FOR "ARexx Function FOR"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}FOR(init,ending_condition,action1,...)@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to define loops. The first argument
    (init) is carried out only once, when the call of the function has
    been just made. The second argument defines the condition of end of
    loop. Finally the third argument as well as the following arguments,
    if they exist, are evaluated with each execution of the loop.

    The use of this function often allows a saving of important time in
    the execution of a script, the number of messages can decrease
    to a significant degree if it is used advisedly.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    FOR (I=0, I<10, I=I+1)
    In this example the @{"variable" LINK Variable} I is initialized to value 0,
    while this value is lower than 10, this value is incremented.

    FOR (I=10, I>0, DELETE(SOURCE,I), I=I-1)
    This formula includes an additional instruction making it
    possible to remove the first 10 entries.

    N=100:FOR (I=0:J=0, I<=N, J=J+I, I=I+1):J
    This formula makes it possible to calculate the sum of the first 100
    numbers. The result of the sum is returned (:J at the end).

    @{I}Note:@{UI} a blocked loop can be stopped by two means: either
    by the maximum number of loops (defined by function @{"security" LINK SECURITY}),
    or while pressing simultaneously on three keys CTRL, ALT
    and ESC.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"WHILE" LINK WHILE}, @{"STOP" LINK STOP}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FREE "ARexx Function FREE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}FREE(tab)@{ub}

    This function releases the contents of a tab. The number of the
    tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the current active
    source tab is treated.

    If the tab contains the history this one is re-initialized (the
    corresponding list is emptied).

    If you want that the tab to be displayed at once use function
    @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY} (useful in a script).
@ENDNODE
@NODE FULLNAME "ARexx Function FULLNAME"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{b}FULLNAME(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to reconstitute the complete name of a
    file, by associating the name of the drawer of the tab and that
    of the name associated with an entry with the specified tab. It
    inserts the separators (/) if necessary.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the active tab which is treated. The number of the entry must lie
    between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null it is the first
    selected entry which is taken into account, if there is one.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"GETNAME" LINK GETNAME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETBITS "ARexx Function GETBITS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETBITS(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the bits of protection associated with an entry
    in the specified tab, in the form of a character string, as they
    appear in the window. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and
    10, if it is null it is the active tab which is treated. The number of
    the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is
    0 it is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if
    there is one of them.

    A null chain can be returned if the tab contains a list of volumes
    or a history for example.

    See also : @{"SETBITS" LINK SETBITS}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETCLASS "ARexx Function GETCLASS"
@TOC Files

    @{b}GETCLASS("filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the @{"class" LINK Classes} related to a file,
    like defined in the preferences.

    If it is a drawer chain [DRAWER] is returned. If it is a file it is
    the name of the class which is associated for him which is returned.
    The name of the file must preferably be complete, i.e. with its
    complete path.

    See also : @{"ACTION" LINK ACTION}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETCOMM "ARexx Function GETCOMM"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETCOMM(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the comment associated with an entry with the
    specified tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if
    it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is 0 it
    is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if there is
    one of them.

    A null chain can be returned if the tab contains a list of volumes
    or a history for example.

    See also :@{"SETCOMM" LINK SETCOMM}, @{"COMMENT" LINK COMMENT}, @{"REQCOMM" LINK REQCOMM}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETDATE "ARexx Function GETDATE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETDATE(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the date associated with an entry with the
    specified tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if
    it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is 0 it
    is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if there is
    one of them.

    A null chain can be returned if the tab contains a list of volumes
    or a history for example.

    See also : @{"SETDATE" LINK SETDATE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETDIR "ARexx Function GETDIR"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETDIR(tab,"path")@{ub}

    This order makes it possible to read a repertory in the specified
    tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10,  if it is 0
    it is the active tab which is treated.

    The returned value is 0 if there no were error.
    Caution: a drawer protected in reading (bit R not validated) does
    not involve any error (it appears simply empty).

	@{i}Examples:@{ui}
	    GETDIR(SOURCE,"RAM:")
	    GETDIR(2,"USB0:")
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETENTRY "ARexx Function GETENTRY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETENTRY (tab, "name")@{ub}

    This order makes it possible to know if a file is present in a
    drawer, or at least in a tab. If it is present, its index in the
    tab is returned (1 for the first of the list, etc...) if not it is
    one 0 which is returned. The number of the tab must lie between 1
    and 10, if it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated.

    The second argument should not include chars such as :
    or / which defines a path, the name of the file alone (or drawer)
    owes only being present.

    Examples of use : see scripts @{"Search" LINK Search.AmiDisk}, @{"MoveArchive" LINK MoveArchive.AmiDisk}, @{"Duplicate" LINK Duplicate.AmiDisk},
    @{"CopyNewer" LINK CopyNewer.AmiDisk}, @{"CmpDrawers" LINK CmpDrawers.AmiDisk}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETNAME "ARexx Function GETNAME"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETNAME(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the name associated with an entry with the
    specified tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if
    it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is 0 it
    is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if there is
    one of them.

    See also : @{"SETNAME" LINK SETNAME}, @{"FULLNAME" LINK FULLNAME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETSIZE "ARexx Function GETSIZE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETSIZE(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the size associated with an entry with the
    specified tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if
    it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is 0 it
    is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if there is
    one of them.

    Caution: the chain comprises special chars, as in the window, if the size
    is higher than 1 Meg.

    A null chain can be returned if the tab contains a list of volumes
    or a history for example.

    Script @{"CalcSize.AmiDisk" LINK ARexx/CalcSize.AmiDisk/MAIN} can be used to convert
    the chain obtained into a number.

    See also : @{"SETTIME" LINK SETTIME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETTIME "ARexx Function GETTIME"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}GETTIME(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function returns the hour associated with an entry with the
    specified tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if
    it is 0 it is the active tab which is treated. The number of the
    entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is 0 it
    is the first selected entry which is taken into account, if there is
    one of them.

    A null chain can be returned if the tab contains a list of volumes
    or a history for example.

    See also : @{"SETTIME" LINK SETTIME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETVAR "ARexx Function GETVAR"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}valeur=GETVAR(VARIABLE)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the contents of an aggregate
    variable, i.e. a variable managed by the principal task and not by one
    of the tasks which carry out the macro-orders. These last lose their
    contents indeed as soon as the task finishes, whereas those managed by
    the principal task keep their contents as long as AmiDisk was not
    stopped. The returned value can be of the numerical type or character
    string, according to the assignment which was made before, using
    function @{"SETVAR" LINK SETVAR}. If no assignment took place, value 0
    is returned.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELP "ARexx Function HELP"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}HELP("node")@{ub}

    Ask of the AmigaGuide assistance. The AmiDisk.guide file must be
    present in the same drawer as the program. It is enough to specify
    the name of a node (name of function for example) to profit from this
    help.

    The returned value is 1 if the function succeeds, 0 if it fails,
    -1 if the node name was too long.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HISTORY "ARexx Function HISTORY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}HISTORY(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the history of the paths having
    been traversed in a tab. The number of the tab must lie between 1
    and 10, if it is null it is the source tab running which is treated.

    If you want that the tab is displayed at once use function
    @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY} (useful in a script).

    A drawer having been read is added to the list only once, if it is
    traversed several times, it will appear only once in the list. This
    list can be emptied in the following way:
	- post the history (by using for example a button comprising
	function HISTORY)
	- click then at once on the Free button or a button using
	function @{"free" LINK FREE}.
	This makes it possible to release a little memory.

    The function returns the number of entries which were read (Version 2.00).

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"ASSIGNS" LINK ASSIGNS}, @{"VOLUMES" LINK VOLUMES}, @{"DEVICES" LINK DEVICES}
@ENDNODE
@NODE IF "ARexx Function IF"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}IF(x, a1, a2)@{UB}

    If X is different from zero, returns a1 if not returns a2. Only a1 OR
    a2 will be evaluated, according to the result of X, note that the
    arguments a1 and a2 can be of any type, they can also call upon other
    functions, including other functions IF.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    IF(A>B,A,B)                 return the maximum value of A and B
    DEF MIN(A,B)=IF(A<B,A,B)    definition MIN function
    IF(REQUEST("Continue ?"),CALL("Script"),0)
@ENDNODE
@NODE ISASCII "ARexx Function ISASCII"
@TOC Files

    @{b}ISASCII ("filename")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know if a file is an ASCII file or
    not. It uses the datatypes to test the contents of the file. If the
    test is concluding the returned value is equal to 1. If the test is
    not good (presence of noncAscii characters) the returned value is null.

    If the file is not found or if an error occurs a message is posted
    (error DOS).

    Example :
	in a macro :
	    IF(ISASCII(FULLNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)))==1,READASC(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),READHEX(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)))
	or in a script :
	    'ISASCII(FULLNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))'
	    if result=1 then 'READASC(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))'
	    else 'READHEX(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE))'
@ENDNODE
@NODE ISDRAWER "ARexx Function ISDRAWER"
@TOC Files

    @{b}ISDRAWER ("name")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know if the argument is a
    drawer (returned value is 1) or a file (return 0).
@ENDNODE
@NODE LANGUAGE "ARexx Function LANGUAGE"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}		Version 2.07

    Return the name of "locale" used by the system. For French the chain
    "french.language" is returned. This function in particular makes it
    possible to internationalize scripts.

    @{i}Example :@{ui}
	'LANGUAGE'
	if result='french.language' then fr=1
	else fr=0
	...
	if fr=1 then 'MESSAGE("Attention, si vous continuez"+CHR(10)+"vous allez perdre vos donnťes !")'
	else 'MESSAGE("Warning, if you continue you are"+CHR(10)+"going to loose all your work !")'
@ENDNODE
@NODE LEN "ARexx Function LEN"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{B}LEN("string")@{UB}

    Return the length of the character string passed in argument.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINES "ARexx Function LINES"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}LINES(tab)@{ub}

    This function returns the number of lines which can be visualized in
    the specified tab. This number depends on dimensions of the window
    and of the police size used to post this list (selected in the
    Preferences). This value is the same one for all the tabs.

    The tab number have to be set between 1 and 10 (or 0
    for the current source tab).

    See also : @{"TOPLIST" LINK TOPLIST}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LISTCOPY "ARexx Function LISTCOPY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}LISTCOPY(tab)@{ub}

    The tab number have to be set between 1 and 10 (or 0
    for the current source tab).

    The list of the drawers and/or files selected in the specified tab
    is copied in an internal buffer.

    When function LISTPAST is called the list of these files and of
    these drawers is copied, these files will be preserved.

    Caution: if one of the files (or a drawer) of the list which was put
    in memory at the time of this operation is removed before the call of
    function @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST}, this operation will fail.

    See also : @{"LISTFREE" LINK LISTFREE}, @{"LISTCUT" LINK LISTCUT}, @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LISTCUT "ARexx Function LISTCUT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}LISTCUT(tab)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the source tab running which will be used.

    The list of the drawers and/or files selected in the specified tab
    is copied in an internal buffer.

    When function LISTPAST is called the list of these files and of these
    drawers is copied, the original files and drawers will then be destroyed.

    Caution: if one of the files (or a drawer) of the list which was put
    in memory at the time of this operation is removed before the call of
    function @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST}, this operation will fail.

    See also : @{"LISTFREE" LINK LISTFREE}, @{"LISTCOPY" LINK LISTCOPY}, @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LISTFREE "ARexx Function LISTFREE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}LISTFREE@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to release the memory occupied by the
    list which was previously memorized by one of orders @{"LISTCOPY" LINK LISTCOPY} or
    @{"LISTCUT" LINK LISTCUT}.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the source tab running which will be used.

    This order can fail if at the same moment another task is using this
    list (locked list).

    See also : @{"LISTCOPY" LINK LISTCOPY}, @{"LISTCUT" LINK LISTCUT}, @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LISTPAST "ARexx Function LISTPAST"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}LISTPAST(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to launch the copy of the list of
    files previously memorized by using one of two functions LISTCOPY or
    LISTCUT. If it is the function LISTCUT which had been created the list
    of the files, those will be removed after their copy, and it list will
    be emptied memory.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the source tab running which will be used.

    Caution: the specified tab must of course contain a valid path (not
    list of volumes, assignments, devices or history).

    If the button "Confirm copies" is marked in @{"prťfťrences" LINK PrefsDisplay}
    the recopy of already existing files will involve the
    opening of a request making it possible either to be unaware of this
    file, or to recopy it, or to stop the operation. The ordering of copy
    can be stopped by pressing key ESC whereas the tab is selected.

    Caution: if you try to copy drawers and files in the drawer where
    these same drawers and files are located, you will obtain surely an
    odd result... in certain cases you will have simply an error message,
    in others you can fill your disc before this message does not appear.

    See also : @{"LISTCOPY" LINK LISTCOPY}, @{"LISTCUT" LINK LISTCUT}, @{"LISTFREE" LINK LISTFREE}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADBAR "ARexx Function LOADBAR"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}LOADBAR("barfile")@{UB}

    Load the toolbar specified. If the bar had been already loaded
    it's passed to the foreground (usefull to uniconify a bar).
    Several bars can be at the same time loaded, if they have not
    the same†name.

    This function returns a null result if the loading occurred well.
    If the last argument is a null chain all the bars present in memory
    passed to the foreground (and reopen if necessary).

    See also : @{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR}, @{"CLOSEBAR" LINK CLOSEBAR}, @{"EDITBAR" LINK EDITBAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOWER "ARexx Function LOWER"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{b}LOWER("string")@{ub}

    This function returns the string passed in argument after having
    converted all the characters in small letters. The source chain is
    not modified, in particular if it acts of a variable.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{b}UPPER@{ub}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MAKEDIR "ARexx Function MAKEDIR"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}MAKEDIR(tab,"dirname")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to create a drawer in the path
    corresponding to the specified tab. There is no creation of icon
    associated with this drawer, use function @{"ADDICON" LINK ADDICON}
    for that. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is
    null it is the tab source which is used. The name of the drawer should
    not naturally comprise : or /.

    If the function makes a success the row of the new entry in
    the list is returned (always higher than 0), this code is that which
    would be returned by function @{"GETENTRY" LINK GETENTRY}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MAKENAME "ARexx Function MAKENAME"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{b}MAKENAME("chemin","nom_fichier")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to reconstitute the complete name of a
    file, by associating the name of a drawer and that of a file. It
    inserts the separators (/) if necessary.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"PATHPART" LINK PATHPART}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MAP "ARexx Function MAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}MAP ("keys", "command")@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to program a macro-order, which will
    be carried out at the time of the support of a certain combination of
    keys. Keys @{B}ALT@{UB}, @{B}SHIFT@{UB} and @{B}CTRL@{UB} can be used
    only or together, to define a combination of keys. You can also use
    the following keys: F1 with F12, DEL, UP, DOWN, RIGHT, LEFT, BS, PAGEUP,
    PAGEDOWN, HOME, END and INSERT. The name of the keys can be specified in
    small letters or in capital letters, indifferently, in the same way for
    the special keys (Shift, alt, ctrl).

    The command can include any other function, it must be included between
    brackets (character string). The definition can start with the sign =,
    the result of macro will then automatically be posted.

    Note that these definitions are saved in the file EnvArc:AmiDisk/Keys
    at the time of an operation of safeguard of @{"Preferences" LINK "Keys"}, and are
    thus recovered at the time of the launching of the program.

    You can also use @{"script" LINK Script} ARexx @{"MapKey" LINK  MapKey.AmiDisk} to
    define a sequence of keys.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    MAP("shift-ctrl-a","GETDIR(SOURCE,""Prog:Projects/Sheets"")")
    MAP("CTRL-)","CALL(""Swap"")")
    MAP("F10","WTOBACK")
    MAP("Shift-Del","DELETE(SOURCE,0)")

    @{I}See also :@{UI}
    @{"READMAP" LINK READMAP}, @{"UNMAP" LINK UNMAP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARK "ARexx Function MARK"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}MARK(tab,entry,...)@{UB}

    Allows to select one or more entries. The number of the tab must lie
    between 1 and 10, if it is null the tab source is used. The
    other arguments must have a value ranging between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.
    This function returns the number of entries which were
    actually selected (the entries which was @{B}already@{UB} selected are
    @{B}not@{UB} counted).
	Examples: MARK(SOURCE,1,2)
		  MARK(DEST,10)

    @{I}Note :@{UI} the call of the function with an argument equal
    to -1 involves the selection of all the entries of the specified
    tab. It then returns the total number of entries. There should then
    be only two arguments:
	Example: MARK(SOURCE, -1)

    The following writing will cause an error (more than two arguments) :
	MARK(SOURCE,1,-1)

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"UNMARK" LINK UNMARK}, @{"FIRSTSEL" LINK FIRSTSEL}, @{"TEST" LINK TEST}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MESSAGE "ARexx Function MESSAGE"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}MESSAGE("string")@{UB}

    Post a request containing the specified message. This text can contain
    line feeds (CHR(10)).

    @{I}Example :@{UI} MESSAGE("This is a"+CHR(10)+"message.")
@ENDNODE
@NODE MOVE "ARexx Function MOVE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}MOVE (source, destination, entry)@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to recopy the specified entries of the
    tab source specified in the tab destination specified. The files
    and the drawers associated with these entries of course are also
    copied. The tabs are normally specified by using functions
    @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE} and @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, but you can specify
    any tab, ranging between 1 and 10. If the operation makes a success
    the source files are destroyed.

    The parameter corresponding to the entry can take the following
    values:
    - if it is a negative number, all the entries of the tab
    source will be copied, that they are or not selected.
    - if this number is null, only the selected entries will be copied.
    - if it is a positive number, only the specified entry will be copied.
    The number of the entry must then lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    The function returns the number of entries which were copied.

    The intervention of any error stops the execution of macro
    normally. There is a warning message if a file is already existing and
    that it is thus replaced by another provided that @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay}
    were suitably fixed, or although function REQOVER returns one 1.

    Examples :
	MOVE(SOURCE,DEST,0)     "classical" command
	MOVE(1,2,-1)            copy all entries from first tab in the second tab

    Nota : the order can succeed only if the TWO tabs are free at the time of
    the call of the function.

    See also : @{"COPY" LINK COPY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEWENTRY "ARexx Function NEWENTRY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}NEWENTRY(tab,"filename")@{ub}

    This command makes it possible to add a file or a repertory to a tab.
    It is useful if a script uses a DOS command to copy a file or a
    drawer in the drawer of the specified tab. This file or this
    drawer owes of course being located in the drawer corresponding
    to the tab. The use of this command makes it possible to avoid reading
    again all the drawer while using the command @{"GETDIR" LINK GETDIR},
    which makes it possible to update the list.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    tab credit source is used.

    If the function makes a success the row of the new entry in the
    list is returned (always higher than 0), this code is that which would
    be returned by function @{"GETENTRY" LINK GETENTRY}. If the file does
    not exist an error is generated, and the entry is not created.

    The various columns of the list are automatically updated (bits, size,
    date, etc...) and the entry is inserted in the list by taking of
    account the order of sorting in use.

    See also : @{"ADDENTRY" LINK ADDENTRY}, @{"REMENTRY" LINK REMENTRY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE OUTPUT "ARexx Function OUTPUT"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}OUTPUT("console definition")@{ub}

    This command is used to define the console which will be used for the
    inputs/outputs of command @{"RUNCLI" LINK RUNCLI}. If this command were
    not carried out command RUNCLI uses the consoles owing to lack of
    AmiDisk (the window of Shell since which AmiDisk was launched, for
    example).

    For a determined task, if the command were already carried out, the
    command will not have any effect, except if you use before the
    command OUTPUT("") which will cause to close the beforehand open
    console, thus allowing the opening of a news.

    This console is usable only by the task which opened it. The console
    is closed at the end of the execution of the associated @{b}task@{ub}.

    Examples :
	OUTPUT("CON:100/100/640/400/AmiDisk output/WAIT/AUTO/CLOSE")
	OUTPUT("CON:0/0/1000/200//AUTO")
	OUTPUT("CON:100/100/640/400/AmiDisk screen window/WAIT/AUTO/CLOSE/SCREENAmiDisk")

    The four numbers which follow CON: the site and dimensions of the
    window determine, one finds then the title which will be posted there,
    followed options available (WAIT involves waiting of an intervention
    of the user to close the window, CLOSE makes it possible to add a
    button of closing to the window, parameter SCREEN makes it possible to
    open the window on the screen having the specified name, if there
    exists).
@ENDNODE
@NODE PARENT "ARexx Function PARENT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}PARENT(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the drawer relative of the
    specified tab. If the way of the tab corresponds to the root of
    volume, it is the list of volumes which is posted.

    The returned value is 0 if there no were error.

    See also : @{"GETDIR" LINK GETDIR}, @{"PATHPART" LINK PATHPART}
@ENDNODE
@NODE PATHPART "ARexx Function PATHPART"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{b}PATHPART("filename")@{ub}

    This function returns the corresponding path in the name of file passed
    in argument. A null chain is returned if this name does not contain
    any element which is appropriate. The treatment and carried out by
    taking of account the characters composing the chain passed in
    argument, no test is let to know if this chain corresponds to a really
    existing way.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	PATHPART("RAM:t")   returns RAM:
	PATHPART("Work:Photos/Meeting/Plan.jpg") returns Work:Photos/Meeting
	DEF GETPARENT(TAB)=GETDIR(TAB,PATHPART(CURRDIR(TAB)))

    See also : @{"MAKENAME" LINK MAKENAME}, @{"PARENT" LINK PARENT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE POS "ARexx Function POS"
@TOC "Traitement†chaÓnes"

    @{b}POS(sub_string,string)@{ub}

    Return the row of the sub_string in the string, if it is, if not
    returns 0 there.

	@{i}Examples :@{ui}
	    POS("s","essai")    returns 2
	    POS("sa","essai")   returns 3
	    POS("y","essai")    returns 0
@ENDNODE
@NODE PROTECT "ARexx Function PROTECT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}PROTECT(tab,entry,"bits")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to fix the bits of protection of a
    drawer or a file. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and
    10, if it is null it is the active tab which is used. The number of
    the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, equal to 0
    (application to all the selected entries) or equal to -1 (application
    to all the entries, which they are selected or not). The bits must be
    specified by using the letter which corresponds to them: H: bit Hold
    S: bit Script P: bit Pure (Rťentrant) a: bit Files R: bit Read
    (Reading) W: bit Write (Writing) E: bit Executable D: bit Delete
    (Erasable)

    Three forms can be used:
	- passage of all the bits having to be positioned
	- passage of the bits having to be added (the chain must start with one +)
	- passage of the bits to be removed (the chain must start with one -)

    The function returns the number of files for which the treatment
    succeeded.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	PROTECT(SOURCE,1,"RWD")
	PROTECT(SOURCE,2,"+A")      add the bit archive to the second entry
	PROTECT(DEST,0,"-E")        remove the bit Executable to all selected entries

    See also : @{"REQBITS" LINK REQBITS}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READASC "ARexx Function READASC"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}READASC(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open the window of ASCII reading.
    The reading uses the class Reaction gadgets/texteditor.gadget, it
    makes it possible to select a part of the text to make cut & paste,
    but it is not managed perfectly if the file comprises too long lines,
    not entering on only one line. Use MultiView if that makes
    problem to you. However this function makes it possible simultaneously
    to read several files without occupying too much of memory, only the
    part posted with the screen is actually read in memory, the file being
    progressively read run. This is particularly interesting for the large
    files.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null, the
    tab source running will be used.

    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry will be read.

    Caution: it is impossible to pass a drawer in argument, that will
    involve an error message.

    The function returns 1 if the user clicked on Continue if not it
    returns 0.

    Examples of use : see scripts  @{"ReadHexa" LINK ReadHexa.AmiDisk} et @{"ReadFiles" LINK ReadFiles.AmiDisk}

    See also : @{"READHEX" LINK READHEX}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READDEF "ARexx Function READDEF"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}READDEF("function")@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to know the definition associated with
    a function. The name of the function passed in argument must appear in
    capital letters, between brackets. This function must of course have
    been beforehand defined using function DEF, if not a null chain is
    returned. You cannot read the built-in definitions, like ABS, ASC,
    etc...

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    READDEF("GETROOT")   return the definition associated with the function
	GETROOT, if it exists, else a null string is returned.

    @{I}See also :@{UI}  @{"DEF" LINK DEF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READHEX "ARexx Function READHEX"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}READHEX(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function opens the request of reading into hexadecimal of one or
    more files. This window comprises, on the left the offset in the file,
    the characters into hexadecimal then their equivalent in ASCII, if
    possible. The files remain all the time open of their reading.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null, the
    tab source running will be used.

    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry will be read.

    @{b}Caution@{ub}: it is impossible to pass a drawer in argument,
    that will involve an error message.

    The function returns 1 if the user clicked on Continue if not it
    returns 0.

    Examples of use : see scripts  @{"ReadHexa" LINK ReadHexa.AmiDisk} et @{"ReadFiles" LINK ReadFiles.AmiDisk}

    See also : @{"READASC" LINK READASC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READMAP "ARexx Function READMAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}READMAP("keys")@{UB}

    This function returns a character string containing the sequence of
    command associated with the combination with keys specified. It thus
    makes it possible to create macros which can be called the ones the
    others. Its vocation is however to check that a sequence already does
    not exist for a combination of keys given, or of reading the macro one
    already programmed in order to publish it (as in script @{"MapKey" LINK MapKey.AmiDisk}).

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
      READMAP("shift-ctrl-a")
      READMAP("CTRL-i")
      READMAP("ALT-Ķ")
      EXEC(READMAP("F1"))   Carry out the command associated with the F1 key

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"MAP" LINK MAP}, @{"UNMAP" LINK UNMAP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REFRESH "ARexx Function REFRESH"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}mode=REFRESH(tab,mode)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    tab credit source will be used, if it is lower than 0 (normally -1)
    it is that one seeks to know the state of the preferences, without
    reference to a particular tab. This function makes it possible to
    fix the state of the fast display flag for the specified tab. If
    the argument mode is higher than 0, this flag is validated, if it is
    null, posting will be slower, but it will be updated after each
    operation, if it is negative the function does not have any effect.

    Return the state of the fast display flag (null result if flag not
    marked, different from 0 if not) in progress in the tab specified
    before the application of the function (or of the preferences if the
    argument corresponding to the tab is equal to -1).

    With the starting of the program, each tab takes the state of the
    fast display flag such as it is defined in the preferences, then
    this function makes it possible to fix this one individually, for each
    tab. If the preferences are modified when using the
    program, the flag is recopied for each tab, except for those
    which are then occupied.

    See also : @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REMENTRY "ARexx Function REMENTRY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}REMENTRY(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to remove an entry (or even several)
    of the specified list. The number of the tab must lie between 1 and
    10, if it is null it is the tab source running which is treated.
    The number of the entry can lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    in which case only the specified entry will be withdrawn. If
    this number is null, all the entries then selected will be withdrawn,
    if it is negative all the entries will be withdrawn, that they are
    selected or not.

    The withdrawn entries will be restored at the time of the use of the
    button to @{"Refresh" LINK RefreshButton} for example.

    Example :
	Removal of the entries not marked in the tab running:
	N=1:WHILE(N<=ENTRIES(0),IF(TEST(0,N)==0,REMENTRY(0,N),N=N+1))

    See scripts @{"LoadHistory" LINK LoadHistory.AmiDisk}, @{"ToLeft" LINK ToLeft.AmiDisk}, @{"ToRight" LINK ToRight.AmiDisk}, @{"Touch" LINK Touch.AmiDisk}, @{"Duplicate" LINK Duplicate.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE RENAME "ARexx Function RENAME"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}RENAME(tab,entry,"name")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to change the name of an entry. The
    number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    active tab is used. The number of the entry must lie between 1 and
    @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null the first selected entry is treated.
    The name should not include some : or / (the file or the
    drawer cannot be moved).
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQACT "ARexx Function REQACT"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQACT (onglet, entry)@{ub}

    If the entry argument is positive or null, this function involves
    the opening of a request which makes it possible to choose one of
    the actions associated with the entry chosen, such as they were
    defined in @{"preferences" LINK Classes}. If the entry argument is
    negative (-1), the requester include ALL the actions.
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is no it is
    the active tab which is used. The number of the entry must lie
    between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null it is the first
    selected entry which will be treated.

    The function @{"ENTRY" LINK ENTRY} take the value of the entry that
    has been specified by the command.

    The returned value is the name of the selected action, if the requester
    is cancelled an empty string ("") is returned.

    See also : @{"ACTION" LINK ACTION}, @{"DOACTION" LINK DOACTION}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQBITS "ARexx Function REQBITS"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQBITS (tab, entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open a request making it possible
    to edit the bits of protection of one or more files (HSPARWED). The
    number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is no it is the
    active tab which is used. The number of the entry must lie between 1
    and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, equal to 0 (application to all the
    selected entries) or equal to -1 (application to all the entries,
    which they are selected or not).

    The function returns the number of files for which the treatment was
    validated and succeeded.

    The command can been unaware of for an entry (Pass button), be applied
    (Validate), be applied to all the remaining entries (All) or cancelled
    (Cancel).

    Note: the bit H (hold?) has an unknown role for me...

    See also : @{"PROTECT" LINK PROTECT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQCOPY "ARexx Function REQCOPY"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}REQCOPY(source, destination, entry)@{UB}

    This function was removed in version 2.00, it is now necessary to use
    command @{"COPY" LINK COPY} by holding account of the result of function
    @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQCOLS "ARexx function REQCOLS"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQCOLS(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open a request where can be fixed
    the @{"widths of columns" LINK ColumnsList} of the specified tab.
    If the user makes a modification to these values the list is
    displayed by holding some account. It is possible to hide a column
    while entering a negative or null value for its width.

    See also : @{"COLUMNS" LINK COLUMNS}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQCOMM "ARexx Function REQCOMM"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQCOMM (tab, entry)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open a request making it possible
    to edit the comments associated with one or more files. You can enter
    a text of 80 characters maximum.
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is
    the active tab which is used. The number of the entry can lie between
    1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, equal to 0 (application to all the selected
    entries) or equal to -1 (application to all the entries, which they
    are selected or not).

    The function returns the number of files for which the treatment was
    validated and succeeded.

    The command can been unaware of for an entry (Pass button), be applied
    (Validate), be applied to all the remaining entries (All) or cancelled
    (Cancel).

    See also : @{"COMMENT" LINK COMMENT}, @{"SETCOMM" LINK SETCOMM}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQFILE "ARexx Function REQFILE"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}REQFILE("titre_requÍte","chemin","fichier")@{UB}

    Open the asl file requester, with the specified title. The request
    opens by exploring the specified path. This path must correspond to that
    of a drawer or a volume.

    Return the name of the selected file or a null chain if the user
    clicks on the Cancel button.

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
	REQFILE("Select a script",DISKPATH+"ARexx","*.AmiDisk")
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQFUNC "ARexx Function REQFUNC"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}REQFUNC ("Title", "string", "Variable")@{ub}

    Post a request comprising the message of specified title, a string
    gadget containing the specified string in second argument allows to
    input a character string. A button located on the right of this chain
    makes it possible to select a function among all those proposed by
    AmiDisk. Two other buttons can be used to import or export a macro
    from/to a file.

    If the user validates his choice, the variable whose name passed in
    third argument is positioned to 1, if not it is positioned to 0. If
    this command is received from a ARexx script, it is a ARexx variable
    which will be initialized whereas if the command is sent since a AmiDisk
    request, it is a AmiDisk variable which will be used.

    The value returned by the function is the chain seized in the request.
    A null chain is always returned if the user cancelled the request.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"REQSTR" link REQSTR}, @{"MapKey" LINK MapKey.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQLIST "ARexx Function REQLIST"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQLIST (title, entry1, ...)@{ub}

    This function allows the opening of a window having the specified
    title. It contains as many lines determined by the arguments which
    follow (entry1, etc...). It returns the number of the entry (1 to
    N) on which the user clicks with the left button of the mouse, or -1
    if the operation is cancelled (click on the button of closing of
    the window).

    If the window could not be open (report lack or other), value 0 is
    returned.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQMOVE "ARexx Function REQMOVE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}REQMOVE(source, destination, entry)@{UB}

    This function was removed in version 2.00, it is now necessary to use
    command @{"COPY" LINK COPY} by holding account of the result of function
    @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQNUM "ARexx Function REQNUM"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQNUM("Title",number,"Variable")@{ub}

    Post a request comprising the message of specified title, a numerical
    gadget containing the number specified in second argument allows to
    seize a whole number. If the user validates his choice, the variable
    whose name passed in third argument is positioned to 1, if not it is
    positioned to 0. If this command is received from a ARexx script, it is
    a ARexx variable which will be initialized whereas if the command is
    sent since a AmiDisk request, it is a AmiDisk variable which will be
    used.

    Example of script :
	'REQNUM("Enter a number",0,"VALID")'
	if valid=1 then do
	    n=result
	    'MESSAGE("You have entered number 'n'")'
	end
	else 'MESSAGE("Operation cancelled")'

    Example of macro :
	N=REQNUM("Enter a number",0,"VALID"):IF(VALID==1,MESSAGE("You have entered "+STR(N)),MESSAGE("Operation cancelled"))

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"REQSTR" link REQSTR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQOVER "ARexx function REQOVER"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQOVER (tab,-1/0/1)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to determine the behavior of the
    program at the time of the use of functions @{"LISTPAST" LINK LISTPAST},
    @{"COPY" LINK COPY} or @{"MOVE" LINK MOVE}.

    The first argument makes it possible to know if the command is carried
    out for all the copies to come, in any tab (it must then be equal to
    -1 in this case, that corresponds to a modification of the adjustment
    of the preferences), if this argument is positive or null the second
    argument is taken into account only for the orders to come in script
    or the pending order.

    If the second argument is equal to 0, the files will be replaced, if
    they already exist, without warning message. If this argument is equal
    to 1, a message will warn the user to require of him to confirm the
    replacement of an existing file by another. If the argument is worth
    -1, no change will be made, this value being used to know the state of
    the function without anything to modify.

    The returned value is equal at the state in force BEFORE the execution
    of the function. The initial state depends on the adjustment made in
    @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay}.

    This function was written to be associated a button of the bistable
    type. The function making it possible to initialize the button is then
    the following one:
	REQOVER(-1,-1)
    whereas the function associated with the button is form:
	REQOVER(-1,REQOVER(-1,-1)?1)

    If you want to use function COPY in a script, without holding account
    of the preferences, you can use something of the kind:
	'STATE=REQOVER(0,0)'        /* Suppress warnings  */
	'COPY(SOURCE,DEST,0)'       /* Copy selected entries */
	'REQOVER(SOURCE,STATE)'     /* Restore previous state */
    In this case the copy will be carried out without warning message
    whatever the adjustment made in the preferences, but this for the
    tabs source and destination then selected, and for this script only.
    All the operations of copies which will follow will take again normal
    operation, i.e. while following the adjustment of the preferences.

    Caution: one should not or not place several buttons with this
    function (in the same bar of tools) because their state will not
    correspond any more all to the state of the function after one of them
    will have been used.

    If the user modifies the preferences the state of the flag will not be
    changed for as much, those defining this state in the starting of the
    program only.

    Examples of use : scripts @{"Copy" LINK Copy.AmiDisk}, @{"CopyNewer" LINK CopyNewer.AmiDisk}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQPREFS "ARexx Function REQPREFS"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQPREFS("D|A|K|M|T|C|B")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open a request of preferences. The
    request which will be open depends on the argument:
	- if it is D it is the request of the adjustments of posting (Display)
	- if it is A it is the request of the classes (and the Actions)
	- if it is K it is the request of the keys (Keyboard)
	- if it is M it is the request of the programmable Menus
	- if it is T it is the request of the icons of the bar the top
	- if it is C it is the request of the icons of the bar of the Center
	- if it is B it is the request of the icons of the bar of bottom

    Only the first letter of the argument is tested, you can thus
    enter REQPREFS("D") or REQPREFS("Display").

    Note that a given request can be open only once, on the other hand
    each one of them can be at the same time open. Certain problems can
    occur, if you change mode of screen whereas certain tasks still turn,
    it is impossible to close the window to reopen it by taking of to
    account this new fashion. The change will take place when no task
    turns more.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQSTR "ARexx Function REQSTR"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}REQSTR("Title","string","Variable")@{ub}

    Post a request comprising the message of specified title, a gadget of
    chain containing the chain specified in second argument allows to
    seize a character string. If the user validates his choice, the
    variable whose name passed in third argument is positioned to 1, if
    not it is positioned to 0. If this command is received from a ARexx
    script, it is a ARexx variable which will be initialized whereas if
    the order is sent since a AmiDisk request, it is a AmiDisk variable
    which will be used.

    Example of script :
	'REQSTR("Enter a name","Smith","VALID")'
	if valid=1 then do
	    nom=result
	    'MESSAGE("You entered the name 'nom'")'
	end
	else 'MESSAGE("Operation cancelled")'

    Example of macro :
	N=REQSTR("Enter a name","Smith","VALID"):IF(VALID==1,MESSAGE("You entered "+N),MESSAGE("Operation cancelled"))

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"REQNUM" link REQNUM}  @{"REQFUNC" link REQFUNC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUEST "ARexx Function REQUEST"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}REQUEST("title")@{UB}

    Post a request with the specified text (there can be several lines of
    text, separated by line feeds), and two buttons YES and NOT. If the
    user clicks on the button YES or presses on ENTER key, this function
    returns 1.

    If the user clicks on the button NO or presses on key ESC, the
    returned value is 0.

    In the event of problem (report lack for example), the returned value
    is negative.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RUNCLI "ARexx Function RUNCLI"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}RUNCLI("command",stack,"path")@{ub}

    This command allows the execution of a DOS command, as if it were entered
    under Shell. The size of the stack cannot be less than 4 KB. The path
    is used like "home directory". You can specify a null chain if it is
    of no importance. The execution of the command is made in a synchronous
    way: it should be waited until it is finished before being able to
    carry out another action, except if you precede the order by 'run '.

    The returned value is the value returned by the called upon command, as
    under Shell (Ex: 20 corresponds to a level of error raised, 0 is OK).

    Examples :
	RUNCLI("c:dir",0,"RAM:")
	RUNCLI("c:dir "+CURRDIR(SOURCE),0,"")
	RUNCLI("NewShell",0,"")
	RUNCLI("SYS:Utilities/MultiView "+GETNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),10000,CURRDIR(SOURCE))
	RUNCLI("run <NIL: >NIL: AUDIO:SimplePlay "+GETNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),10000,CURRDIR(SOURCE))

    See also :
	@{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT}, @{"RUNWB" LINK RUNWB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE RUNWB "ARexx Function RUNWB"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}RUNWB("command","argument","path")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to launch a command as if the user had
    clicked on an icon of Workbench. If it is a drawer it is open on
    the window of Workbench. The execution of the command is made in an
    asynchronous way: it is not necessary to wait until it is finished
    before being able to carry out another action. If the argument is a
    null chain ("") it will be ignored. The returned value is 0 if there
    no were error.

    Examples :
       RUNWB("SYS:Utilities/MultiView",GETNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),CURRDIR(SOURCE))
       RUNWB("Travail:AmiCAD/AmiCAD",FULLNAME(SOURCE,FIRSTSEL(SOURCE)),"Travail:AmiCAD")
       RUNWB("","",CURRDIR(SOURCE))     Open the window of the drawer source on Workbench

    See also :
	@{"RUNCLI" LINK RUNCLI}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCRNAME "ARexx Function SCRNAME"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}SCRNAME@{ub}

    This function returns the name of the screen on which is open AmiDisk.
    It can be used to open to Shell one a console on this screen.

    Example of script :
	'SCRNAME'
	screen=result
	'OUTPUT("CON:100/100/640/400/AmiDisk/WAIT/CLOSE/SCREEN'screen'")'
@ENDNODE
@NODE SECURITY "ARexx Function SECURITY"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}SECURITY(loops)@{UB}

    This function determines the maximum @{B}number of loops@{UB} which can
    be carried out by one of functions @{"FOR" LINK FOR} or @{"WHILE" LINK WHILE}.
    This makes it possible to leave the loops without end rather
    simply. The default value is equal to 500. You can enter a value going
    of 1 until 2^31-1 (2147483647). The function returns the value in
    progress before its execution. If the returned value is negative, it
    is that the function could not modify the current value, the access to
    the programmable data being blocked by another task.

    You can give to this function an argument of great value without
    fearing blocking, it is effect possible to stop a loop while
    pressing simultaneously on three keys CTRL, ALT and ESC, when
    the tab corresponding to the task is active.

    If the value passed in argument is null only the current value is
    returned, without modification.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SELECT" "ARexx Function SELECT"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{B}SELECT ("title", "button1"...)@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to open a box of request comprising a
    variable number of buttons, comprising each one a text chosen by the
    user. If the user clicks on one of these buttons, the function returns
    the row of the button (while starting with value 1 for the first, 2
    for the second, etc...). At least two arguments should naturally be
    given.

    If the returned value is negative or null, it is that the user pressed
    on the right button or the Esc key, or although the request could not
    be open.

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    SELECT("Number of files ?","10 files","20 files","Select...")
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETBITS "ARexx Function SETBITS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    This function makes it possible to assign the chain specified to the
    specified entry (third column of the list).
    The number of the tab must normally lie between 1 and 10,
    if it is null the tab active source is used.
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry is used, if any.

    Caution: this function changes the chain associated with the entry
    without changing the bits of the file or the drawer which can be
    associated for it. To change the bits of the file, it is necessary to
    use the function PROTECT (which also updates the list). The chain of
    the bits must respect format "HSPARWED", each one of these letters
    being able to be replaced by an indent (-).

    See also : @{"GETBITS" LINK GETBITS}, @{"PROTECT" LINK PROTECT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETBUFF "ARexx Function SETBUFF"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}SETBUFF(tab,size)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read and/or know the size of the
    plug used for the operations on disc. A too important size involves in
    particular problems on the level of keys USB. Caution: the value fixed
    by this function is not saved in the preferences, use the @{"request" LINK PrefsDisplay} for
    this purpose to fix this value at the starting of the program.

    The size cannot be lower than 4096 bytes, if the size passed in
    argument is lower than this value, the value in progress will remain
    unchanged.

    The function always returns the value which was into in progress
    BEFORE the application of the function. To know this value without
    changing it, use thus for example:
	'SETBUFF(SOURCE,0)'
	size=result

    Macro interesting makes it possible to use a particular size
    for a given peripheral:
	SETBUFF(SOURCE,32768):GETDIR(SOURCE,"USB0:")
    This order makes it possible to initialize the tab
    running with a buffer of 32ko, then of launching the reading of the
    repertory of peripheral USB0: (in the event a key USB), thus this
    peripheral could be read in full safety in this tab. It is enough
    to associate this command a menu or a button to launch this one.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETCOMM "ARexx Function SETCOMM"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SETCOMM(tab,entry,"comment")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign the comment specified to the
    specified entry (sixth column of the list). The number of the tab
    must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is the tab source
    running which will be used.

    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry will be treated, if any.

    Caution: this function changes the comment of the entry without
    changing that of the file or the drawer which can be associated for
    him. Use the function COMMENT if you must also change the comment
    associated with a file.

    There is no checking on the validity of the comment which is made
    (length, presence of chars authorized or not...).

    See also : @{"GETCOMM" LINK GETCOMM}, @{"COMMENT" LINK COMMENT}, @{"REQCOMM" LINK REQCOMM}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETDATE "ARexx Function SETDATE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SETDATE(tab,entry,"date")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign the date specified to the
    specified entry (fourth column of the list). The number of the tab
    must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is the tab source
    running which will be used..
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry will be treated, if any.

    Caution: this function changes the date of the entry without changing
    that of the file or the drawer which can be associated for him. The
    date must be with the format chosen in the preferences to post those
    (the examples are given for the date of November 20, 2006):
	AmigaDOS (20-Nov-06),
	International (06-Nov-20),
	American (11-20-06),
	Canadian (20-11-06),
	locale (20/11/2006),
	ISO9601 (2006-11-20).

    See also : @{"GETDATE" LINK GETDATE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETNAME "ARexx Function SETNAME"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SETNAME(tab,entry,"name")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign the name specified to the
    specified entry (first column of the list). The number of the tab
    must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is 0 it is the tab source
    running which will be used. The number of the entry must lie between 1
    and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null the first selected entry
    will be treated.

    Caution: this function changes the name of the entry without
    re-electing the file or the drawer which can be associated for him. It
    there no checking on the validity of the name which is made (length,
    presence of natures authorized or not...), only the null chains ("")
    involve an error.

    See also : @{"GETNAME" LINK GETNAME}, @{"GETENTRY" LINK GETENTRY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETSIZE "ARexx Function SETSIZE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SETSIZE(tab,entry,"size")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign the size specified to the
    specified entry (second column of the list).
    The number of the tab must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is 0
    it is the tab source running which will be used.
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null the first selected entry will be treated.

    Caution: this function changes the size associated with the entry
    without checking if the file or the drawer which can be associated
    to it has really this size. It there no checking on the validity of
    the chain which is made (length, presence of natures authorized or
    not), format...

    See also : @{"GETSIZE" LINK GETSIZE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETTAB "ARexx Function SETTAB"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}SETTAB(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to choose the active tab, it is
    equivalent to a click of the user on a tab, the specified tab
    becomes the tab source. The number of the tab must normally lie
    between 1 and 10.
    The returned value always corresponds to the number
    of the tab which was active before the call of the function.
    To know the number of the active tab use the writing SETTAB(0).

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	SETTAB(IF(SOURCE<10,SOURCE+1,1))    To pass to the following tab
	SETTAB(IF(SOURCE>1,SOURCE-1,10))    To pass to the previous tab
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETTIME "ARexx Function SETTIME"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SETTIME(tab,entry,"time")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign the hour specified to the
    specified entry (fifth column of the list). The number of the tab
    must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is null it is the tab source
    running which will be used. The number of the entry must lie between 1
    and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}, if it is null the first selected entry
    will be treated.

    Caution: this function changes the hour of the entry without changing
    that of the file or the drawer which can be associated for him. The
    hour must be with the format chosen in the preferences to post those
    (the examples are given for 10 p.m., seventeen minutes and thirty-three
    seconds:
	AmigaDOS (22:17:33),
	International (22:17:33),
	Amťricain (22:17:33),
	Canadien (22:17:33),
	locale (22h17),
	ISO9601 (22:17:33).

    See also : @{"GETTIME" LINK GETTIME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETVAR "ARexx Function SETVAR"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}SETVAR(VARIABLE,value)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign a value to an aggregate
    variable, i.e. a variable managed by the principal task and not by one
    of the tasks which carry out the macro-orders. These last lose their
    contents indeed as soon as the task finishes, whereas those managed by
    the principal task keep their contents as long as AmiDisk was not
    stopped. The value can be of the numerical type or character string,
    with the choice. If the first affected value is a number, it will be
    then impossible to assign character strings to this variable (and
    conversely).

    The access to these variables is made under the control of a
    semaphore, which prohibits the simultaneous modification of the same
    variable by two tasks (what could make their reading hazardous).

    See also : @{"GETVAR" LINK GETVAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SGN "ARexx Function SGN"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}SGN(number)@{UB}

    Return 1 if the argument is positive, -1 if it is negative, zero if it
    is null.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEIGHT "ARexx Function SHEIGHT"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}SHEIGHT@{UB}

    This function returns the height of the current screen. It does not
    require any argument.

    @{B}See also:@{UB} @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SORT "ARexx Function SORT"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SORT(tab,order)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to determine the order of sorting of
    the entries in a tab. The second argument makes it possible to
    choose this order, its value determines the order as follows;
	0: alphabetical order of names
	1: sorting by increasing size
	2: sorting by date, while starting with the oldest
	3: alphabetical order reverses names
	4: sorting by decreasing size
	5: sorting by date, while starting with most recent
    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the tab
    credit source is used.

    The number corresponding to the order of sorting used previously is
    returned by the function. Use order SORT(TAB, -1) to know this
    order without modifying it.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SOURCE "ARexx Function SOURCE"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}SOURCE@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the tab source. For information,
    the tabs are numbered from 1 to 10, on the basis of the left towards
    the line.

    When a script is launched, this value remains constant, even if the
    user changes active tab before script does not finish. Use function
    CURRSRC if you want to know the number of the tab source at a given
    moment.

    To know if this tab is free, use function @{"STATUS" LINK STATUS}.

    The use of this function does not block the tab.

    @{B}See also:@{UB} @{"CURRSRC" LINK CURRSRC}, @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, @{"CURRDEST" LINK CURRDEST}
@ENDNODE
@NODE STATUS "ARexx Function STATUS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}STATUS (tab)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    tab credit source is used.
    This function makes it possible to know
    if a tab is occupied or not. The returned value can take the three
    values which follow:
	0: the tab is free,
	1: the tab is already reserved by the task which calls upon the function
	-1: the tab is blocked by another task, it will be thus impossible
	    to access it.

    At the beginning of a script, the test making it possible to know if a
    tab is available can take the following form:
	'STATUS('tab')'
	if result < 0 then do
	    'MESSAGE("Tab is busy")'
	    exit
	end
    Generally the index of the tab will be provided by one of the
    functions @{"SOURCE" LINK SOURCE}, @{"DEST" LINK DEST}, @{"CURRSRC" LINK CURRSRC} ou @{"CURRDEST" LINK CURRDEST}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STOBACK "ARexx Function STOBACK"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}STOBACK@{UB}

    This function makes pass the screen of AmiDisk in background. It does
    not require any argument.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"STOFRONT" LINK STOFRONT} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE STOFRONT "ARexx Function STOFRONT"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}STOFRONT@{UB}

    This function makes pass the screen of AmiDisk in the foreground. It
    does not require any argument.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"STOBACK" LINK STOBACK} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE STOP "ARexx Function STOP"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}STOP@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to stop a loop @{"FOR" LINK FOR} or
    @{"WHILE" LINK WHILE} before its term. It does not have any effect
    apart from a loop.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STR "ARexx Function STR"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}STR(number)@{UB}

    Return the character string corresponding to a number. The base used
    for conversion is base 10 (decimal).
@ENDNODE
@NODE SUBS "ARexx Function SUBS"
@TOC Traitement†chaÓnes

    @{b}SUBS("string", position, length)@{ub}

    Return a subset of the chain passed in argument. This subset
    starts with the character specified by the second argument,
    and includes the number of characters given by the third
    argument.

	@{i}Example:@{ui}
	    SUBS("Texte",3,2)   returns xt

    You can define the traditional functions RIGHT and LEFT starting
    from this function (see @{"DEF" LINK DEF}):
	DEF RIGHT(STRING,N) = SUBS(STRING,LEN(STRING)-N+1,N)
	DEF LEFT(STRING,N) = SUBS(STRING,1,N)
@ENDNODE
@NODE SWIDTH "ARexx Function SWIDTH"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}SWIDTH@{UB}

    This function returns the width of the current screen. It does not
    require any argument.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TABS "ARexx Function TABS"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}TABS@{ub}

    This function return the number of tabs that are used on
    each side id the main window. This number can be set using
    the @{"TABS" LINK Lancement} tooltype, its default value is 5,
    but it can be set between 1 and 10 (included).
@ENDNODE
@NODE TEST "ARexx Function TEST"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}TEST(tab,entry)@{UB}

    Allows to know if an entry is @{B}selected@{UB} or not.
    The number of the tab must normally lie between 1 and 10, if it is 0
    it is the tab source running which will be used.
    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    The function returns 1 if the entry is selected, 0 in the contrary
    case.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"FIRSTSEL" LINK FIRSTSEL}, @{"MARK" LINK MARK}, @{"UNMARK" LINK UNMARK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TIME "ARexx Function TIME"
@TOC "Divers"

    @{b}TIME(seconds)@{ub}

    Return the current hour, if the argument is nonnull, the seconds are
    included. The format used depends on the adjustment carried
    out in @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay} for the format of the date.

	@{i}Examples:@{ui}
	    TIME(0)     returns 23:24
	    TIME(1)     returns 23:24:27

	@{i}See also:@{ui} @{"DATE" LINK DATE}, @{"SETTIME" LINK SETTIME}, @{"GETTIME" LINK GETTIME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TITLE "ARexx Function TITLE"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}TITLE (tab, "Title")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to post a message in the bar of state
    (in bottom of the window). This message is unobtrusive if the user
    clicks in the window or if an operation takes place in this tab. The
    message is posted only when the tab is active. The call of the
    function with the second argument equal to a null chain involves the
    update of the statistics.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR "ARexx Function TOOLBAR"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}TOOLBAR(index)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know how much toolbars are present
    in memory and which are their respective names. If the index is null,
    the number of bars is returned. If the index lies between 1 and this
    number, the name of the bar is corresponding returned. If the index is
    negative the bar is hidden.

    See also : @{"LOADBAR" LINK LOADBAR}, @{"CLOSEBAR" LINK CLOSEBAR}, @{"EDITBAR" LINK EDITBAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TOPLIST "ARexx Function TOPLIST"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}position = TOPLIST (tab, position)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is 0 it is
    the tab source running which will be used.

    This function makes it possible to modify or know the position of the
    first entry which is posted in the list associated with a tab. The
    first position has as an index 0. If you want to know the current
    position without modifying it use a negative argument for the
    position.

    The returned value is always equal to the position in progress before
    the call of the function.

    Examples of macros :
	- to scroll the active list one line up :
	TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)-1)
	- to scroll the active list one line down :
	TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)+1)
	- to scroll the active list ten lines up :
	N=TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)-10:IF(N<0,N=0,N):TOPLIST(SOURCE,N)
	- to scroll the active list ten lines down :
	TOPLIST(SOURCE,TOPLIST(SOURCE,-1)+10)
	- to select the previous entry :
	IF(SOURCE>0,S=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),IF(S>1,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,S-1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,S-2),0)),0)
	- to view the top of the list :
	TOPLIST(SOURCE,0)
	- to view the end of the list :
	TOPLIST(SOURCE,100000)
	- to extend the zone of selection to the top :
	IF(SOURCE>0,S=FIRSTSEL(SOURCE):IF(S==0,MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),IF(S>1,MARK(SOURCE,S-1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,S-2),0)),0)
	- to select the fist entry of the list :
	IF(SOURCE>0,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,1):TOPLIST(SOURCE,0),0)
	- to select the last entry of the list :
	IF(SOURCE>0,UNMARK(SOURCE,-1):MARK(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)):TOPLIST(SOURCE,ENTRIES(SOURCE)),0)

    See also : @{"LINES" LINK LINES}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNFILTER "ARexx Function UNFILTER"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}UNFILTER(tab,"pattern")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to filter the entries of a tab. The
    files corresponding to the reason are unselected. The pattern
    can include all the generic characters used by AmigaDOS (#?*[])...
    The number of the tab must be set between 1 and 10, if it is
    null it is the active tab which is used.

    The function returns the number of entries corresponding to the search
    criterion which were found, that they are beforehand marked or not.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	UNFILTER(SOURCE,"*.c")
	UNFILTER(DEST,"*.[cho]")
	UNFILTER(0,"#?")    unselect all the entries of the current source tab

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"FILTER" LINK FILTER}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNLOCK "ARexx Function UNLOCK"
@TOC Interactivitť

    @{b}UNLOCK(tab)@{ub}

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is 0 it is
    the active tab which is used.

    This command makes it possible to release the access to a tab, before
    script or the macro-command does not finish. It must be used with
    precaution, only if you are sure not to modify the contents of the
    list with script in progress.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNMAP "ARexx Function UNMAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}UNMAP("keys")@{UB}

    This function makes it possible to cancel the programming of
    macro-command, associated a certain combination of keys. Keys
    ALT, SHIFT and CTRL can be used to define the key.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
      UNMAP("shift-ctrl-a")
      UNMAP("ctrl-shift-a")
      UNMAP("CTRL-)")
      UNMAP("ALT-Ķ")
      UNMAP("F2")

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"MAP" LINK MAP}, @{"READMAP" LINK READMAP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNMARK "ARexx Function UNMARK"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{B}UNMARK(tab,entry,...)@{UB}

    Cancel the marking of the specified entries. The numbers of entries
    must have their values ranging between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES}.

    The number of the tab must be set between 1 and 10, if it is null the
    command applies to the current source tab.

    Return the number of selections having been cancelled.

    @{I}Note:@{UI} the call of the function with an argument equal to -1
    involves the cancellation of the selection of all the entries of the
    specified tab.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"MARK" LINK MARK}, @{"TEST" LINK TEST}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UPPER "ARexx Function UPPER"
@TOC "Traitement†chaÓnes"

    @{b}UPPER("string")@{ub}

    Return the character string converted in capital letters. The
    string passed in argument is not modified.

	@{i}See also:@{ui}
	    @{"LOWER" LINK "LOWER"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE VAL "ARexx Function VAL"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}VAL("string")@{UB}

    Return the numerical value corresponding to the character string
    passed in argument. Only the characters corresponding to whole numbers
    are taken into account. The number must appear in decimal form,
    except if it is preceded by the prefix $, which announces that it
    acts of a number in hexadecimal form.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
      VAL("14")       return 14
      VAL("14.3")     return 14
      VAL("$5F")      return 95 ($ specify a hexadecimal string)

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"STR" LINK STR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE VERSION "ARexx Function VERSION"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}VERSION@{UB}

    This function returns the number of version of the program, it does
    not require any argument (Warning : the result is a string of chars,
    not a number).

    @{i}Example of script:@{ui}
    'VERSION'
    if result < 1.05 then do
	'MESSAGE("This version of the program"+CHR(10)+"can''t be used.")'
	exit
    end
    ...
@ENDNODE
@NODE VOLUMES "ARexx Function VOLUMES"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}VOLUMES(tab)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to read the list of volumes in a
    tab. Volumes are read by using their name.

    The number of the tab must be set between 1 and 10, if it is nul
    the source tab which will be used.

    If you want that the tab to be redisplayed at once use function
    @{"DISPLAY" LINK DISPLAY}; if not this posting will take place at the
    end of the task.

    The function returns the number of entries which were read (Version
    2.00).

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"ASSIGNS" LINK ASSIGNS}, @{"DEVICES" LINK DEVICES}, @{"HISTORY" LINK HISTORY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WBINFO "ARexx Function WBINFO"
@TOC Gestion†des†entrťes

    @{b}WBINFO(tab,entry)@{ub}

    This function allows the opening of the request of information of
    Workbench for one or more entries in a tab.

    The number of the tab must lie between 1 and 10, if it is null, the
    tab source running will be used.

    The number of the entry must lie between 1 and @{"ENTRIES" LINK ENTRIES},
    if it is null information will relate to the drawer
    associated with this tab.

    The tab must have a list of drawers and/or files so that the command
    ends. A list (volumes, devices, history...) will cause an error.

    Script @{"WBInfo.AmiDisk" LINK WBInfo.AmiDisk} can be called so that
    this function treats each selected entry, in turn.

    Note: this function can be used to rename a file (or a drawer) by
    using the cell of the name in the request of Workbench, then the Save
    button. Unfortunately the function does not return any value to make
    it possible to know what was carried out. The advantage of this
    method is that the associated info file will be renammed also (if
    it exists, but the list will not be updated).
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHEIGHT "ARexx Function WHEIGHT"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}WHEIGHT@{UB}

    Return the height of the main window.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"WWIDTH" LINK WWIDTH}, @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}, @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHILE "ARexx Function WHILE"
@TOC Maths

    @{B}WHILE(end,action1,...)@{UB}

    This function is identical to the @{"FOR" LINK FOR} command, it misses this function
    just the first argument. The initialization of @{"variables" LINK Variable} tested will
    have thus being carried out before.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SECURITY" LINK SECURITY}, @{"STOP" LINK STOP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WTOBACK "ARexx Function WTOBACK"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}WTOBACK@{UB}

    Send the current window in background

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}, @{"STOBACK" LINK STOBACK}, @{"STOFRONT" LINK STOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WTOFRONT "ARexx Function WTOFRONT"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}WTOFRONT@{UB}

    Send the current window to the foreground.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK}, @{"STOBACK" LINK STOBACK}, @{"STOFRONT" LINK STOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WWIDTH "ARexx Function WWIDTH"
@TOC Divers

    @{B}WWIDTH@{UB}

    Return the width of the main window.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"WHEIGHT" LINK WHEIGHT}, @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}, @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Buttons "The buttons"
@TOC MAIN
    The main window has an icon allowing to @{"close" LINK Iconify} it,
    in top on the right, on the left of the traditional buttons
    making it possible to change the size of the window or to pass
    it ahead or in background.

    Objects associated to each list (left and right) :
	@{"   Source/Destination   " LINK Active}
	@{"    Path 1...           " LINK Onglets}
	@{"Sort " LINK SortButton}  @{"Refresh" LINK RefreshButton}  @{"Free" LINK FreeTab}
	@{"   Active path          " LINK Path}
	@{"   List                 " LINK ListView}
	@{"   Informations         " LINK Informations}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Iconify "Iconifying the main window"
@TOC Buttons

    The main window of AmiDisk can be closed only if no task turns,
    indeed those use certain resources related to the lists. When the
    window is closed, it can be reopen while clicking twice on the
    @{"icon" LINK AppIcon} located on Workbench.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Onglets "Tabs"
@TOC Buttons

    Each list can be associated five tabs. It is enough to click on one
    of the tabs (Path 3 for example) to activate it. The contents of
    the list are then updated to correspond to this tab. You can change
    the active tab at any time, in particular if one of the tabs is
    associated a particularly long task, like when copying drawers and
    files. When a tab is busy the associated list is grayed to show
    that it is impossible to select new entries there.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Path "Paths associated to tabs"
@TOC Buttons

    The cell of text contains the way associated with the active tab.
    You can enter a path there, but the character ':' must be included
    obligatorily there, if not you will have a warning message (incorrect
    drawer or File name).

    You can choose the active path while clicking initially on one of the
    buttons Devices, Assigns or Volumes, then while clicking on one of the
    entries associated in the list.

    The button located on the left of the cell of text is used to go up
    with the drawer relative.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Active "Source/destination tab"
@TOC Buttons

    These indicators are used to show which is the active tab (source
    tab) and which is the destination tab for certain commands, as for
    the copies of files or some user commands.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SortButton "Sorting lists of drawers and files"
@TOC Buttons

    This button makes it possible to choose the sort criterion of the list
    associated with the active tab (each tab keeps its own sort
    criteria).
    @{b}Name+@{ub}  corresponds to the alphabetical order of the names of drawers then files
    @{b}Size+@{ub}  corresponds to an ascending order by considering the sizes of files
    @{b}Date+@{ub}  corresponds to the order of the dates while starting with oldest
    @{b}Name-@{ub}  corresponds contrary to the alphabetical order of the names of drawers then files
    @{b}Size+@{ub}  corresponds to a descending order by considering the sizes of files
    @{b}Date+@{ub}  corresponds to the order of the dates while starting with most recent
    @{b}None@{ub}   the entries are added progressively with their reading

    Note: you can also click in the bar top of the list
    (containing the titles of the columns) to modify the order of the
    sorting. If you click on the title "Name" the sorting will carry out
    by name (growing, then decreasing, alternatively).

    See also : ARexx function @{"SORT" LINK SORT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RefreshButton "Refresh button"
@TOC Buttons

    This button makes it possible to read again the drawer associated with
    the active tab. It can be useful after having carried out a user command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FreeTab "Free button"
@TOC Buttons

    This button makes it possible to release the memory associated with
    the contents of a list, by emptying this list. Attention, it is
    impossible to recover these contents.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ListView "List of drawers and files"
@TOC Buttons

    AmiDisk manages two lists of files (or 10...). The list of left is
    associated to tabs 1 to 5, that of right-hand side to tabs 6 to 10.
    You can choose the active tab constantly while clicking on its name,
    or by using function @{"SETTAB" LINK SETTAB}.

    A list comprises the following columns:
	- Name (drawer or file)
	- Size (for the files only)
	- Bits (HSPARWED: hold, script, pure, file, read, write, executable, delete)
	- Date
	- Time
	- Comment
    For the lists of devices, volumes and assignments, only the
    Name column is used, and it is impossible to select several entries.
    A click on one of these entries involves indeed its immediate
    validation, the associated drawer being read immediately.

    For a "normal" list (drawers or files) it is possible to select
    several entries in order to apply an order for each one of them. The
    names of drawers are preceded by a mark, it is enough to click above
    to enter this drawer.

    You can change the width of each column using the mouse while clicking
    on the vertical lines of separation and by moving them, while
    maintaining the button supported. These adjustments can be safeguarded
    using the @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay} requester.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UserButtons "Preferences buttons user"
@TOC Preferences

    It is possible to lay out three @{"toolbars" LINK BarreOutils} containing buttons
    in the window of AmiDisk: in top, in the center and in bottom.
    The central bar is vertical whereas the others are horizontal.
    To edit these buttons, it is enough to use the menu
    @{"Project/Preferences" LINK Preferences} or to click on a button
    using the @{"REQPREFS" LINK REQPREFS} function.

    To edit the top toolbar :
	REQPREFS("T")
    To edit the bar of the center:
	REQPREFS("C")
    To edit the bar of bottom :
	REQPREFS("B")
@ENDNODE
@NODE BarreOutils "User buttons Preferences"
@TOC MAIN

    The toolbars, which they are internal or external, can contain
    programmable buttons by the user.

    The toolbars can integrate graphic @{"icons" LINK Icons} or text
    (one of both, or both unit) associated a command programmed by the
    user. It is possible to define horizontal or vertical bars (the
    principal window of AmiDisk has two horizontal and a vertical). It is
    possible to use external bars, which are thus not in the window of
    AmiDisk, but in a separate window (in an unlimited number). Each bar
    can contain up to ten lines of icons, with a maximum of 256 icons for
    each line...

    If the number of icons is too important to hold in the bar it
    is possible to make scroll the icons towards the right-hand side or the
    left while clicking on an icon with the left button of the mouse while
    having supported on one of the Shift keys, the displacement of the
    mouse then involves the icons on the same side. It is unfortunately
    impossible to create an elevator to make scroll the icons, because
    Speedbar has a bug, which prohibits its correct operation (dixit
    autodocs!). I have for my part lost some hours to try to make
    function such a device correctly, without success...

    At the time of their @{"editing" LINK EditBar} the toolbars can be
    modified by using the menus which are attached to the window
    comprising the icons. At the time of their use the external bars can
    pass from the horizontal type to the vertical type, or vice versa,
    simply by using the menu which is attached to them.

    @{b}Note:@{ub} the external toolbars have a button on the right title bar,
    enabling them to be reduced (iconified) of a click of mouse,
    which makes them very practical. A macro, a button or a new click
    of mouse on the icon brings back them continuation on the
    screen, which avoids charging them as of launching of the program,
    which can take time, and which takes place on the screen. The command
    making it possible to reopen all the iconified bars is of form
    LOADBAR(""), this command can be associated to a key
    (Alt-T by default) or to a button.

    See also : functions @{"LOADBAR" LINK LOADBAR}, @{"EDITBAR" LINK EDITBAR}, @{"CLOSEBAR" LINK CLOSEBAR} and @{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditBar "Editing a toolbar"
@TOC BarreOutils

    The toolbars are edited by a separate task of AmiDisk, making it
    possible the program to work without problem at the same time.
    The window comprising the icons, if there is, is attached to a
    menu allowing various operations:
	- Project menu to save, load, close the bar
	- Line/column to choose the type (horizontal or vertical), to
	add or remove lines of icons
	- Button to add or remove buttons in the current line.

    The current line is selected while clicking on a button of the line
    (the request allowing the edition of the button is then open).

    For @{"editing a button" LINK EditButton} already existing  it is
    enough to click above with the left button.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Informations "Informations on bottom of lists"
@TOC Buttons

    This zone is used to give various information. In normal time, when
    the contents of a drawer are posted, the program posts the number of
    bytes available on selected volume, then the quantity of selected
    bytes, the number of drawers and the number of files composing this
    selection.

    At the time of a copy the bar is used as bar of progression, for the
    important files. The names of the drawers or the files copied or
    erased are also posted at the time of the operations of copy,
    displacement, obliteration. The bar of progression is managed only for
    the files whose size is higher than that of the plug of copy.

    Certain scripts can post information in this zone by using function
    @{"TITLE" LINK TITLE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DoubleClick "Button Double Click"
@TOC Buttons

    This button makes it possible to choose if a double click
    launches an action or not. If it is marked, a double click on an
    entry automatically launches the first action associated with this
    entry. In this mode it is necessary to use a Shift key to select
    several entries or to make slip the cursor by maintaining the button
    left supported.

    When this button is not marked each new click on an entry allows
    to (un)select the corresponding entry. A double click does
    not exert then any particular action, the entry being found
    alternatively selected or not.

    This button is initialized with the starting of AmiDisk by taking of
    account the adjustment carried out in @{"preferences" LINK PrefsDisplay}.
    The behavior of the program can then be modified by
    using a bistable button using function @{"DBLCLICK" LINK DBLCLICK}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Aide "On-line help"
@TOC "MAIN"

    On line help can be used at any moment using the AmiDisk.guide
    file. This file must be located in the same drawer than AmiDisk.

    To launch this help, you can press the HELP key, or select a
    menu and press this key at the same moment. Some requesters
    have also a HELP button.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ProblŤmes "Resolution of problems"
@TOC "MAIN"

    Launching of a ARexx script the configuration of a ARexx script in the
    preferences can be done in two ways:
	- the action is of the NoCLI type (or CLI), the command is then of the type:
	    rx script [F]
	Script corresponds of course in the name of script to carry out, with the path
	so necessary BUT WITHOUT EXTENSION REXX. If this extension is present,
	oddly the arguments badly passed to script.
	- the action is of the type ARexx, the order does not include order rx.
	The preceding remarks apply in the same way.

    Opening of Shell
	Use a command of the form:
	    RUNCLI("NewShell",0,"path")
	This command can be associated a combination of keys in order to
	easily launch Shell which inherits the way of the current tab : :
	    RUNCLI("NewShell",0,CURRDIR(SOURCE))
@ENDNODE
@NODE Bugs "BUG(s) ?   (yes! surely... (unfortunately!))"
@TOC MAIN

    This program required much work for me also I would kindly request to
    you to be lenient as for the always possible errors occurring at the
    time of its use. I would be grateful to you for agreeing to @{"inform" LINK "Auteur"}
    me if you note one or several anomalies.
    Translation of the guide from french to english has been done
    using Amitex and BabelDoc, errors are always possible, as I am
    not an english user.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Historique "Program history"
@TOC MAIN

Version 2.02	October 2008
	New task handler modified (very improbable bug in case of low
	memory). Enter and Return keys are now programmable.
	Buttons Format, Refresh and Free removed (Replaced by some
	programmables buttons in toolbar).
	OS4.1 bug correction (Speedbar crash when activating a speedbar
	gadget while help is enabled in window title). New bubbles helps
	for toolbars.
	New @{"CMP" LINK CMP} function. New @{"CmpFiles" LINK CmpFiles.AmiDisk} script.
	New @{"ISDRAWER" LINK ISDRAWER} function.
	Compilation of the program for OS 3.9.

Version 2.01	January 2008
	Selection of tabs number (Tooltype @{"TABS" LINK Lancement}), new function @{"TABS" LINK TABS}.
	New keyboard shortcuts and names for buttons, to make it possible
	to found them easily.
	New logo name (AmiDiskLogo) to make it possible to change the
	image (png, jpg...)

Version 2.00	July 2007
	Addition of functions @{"DBLCLICK" LINK DBLCLICK}, @{"REQOVER" LINK REQOVER}, @{"REQACT" LINK REQACT}, @{"EXIT" LINK EXIT}.
	Suppression of functions MOVE, REQMOVE. Entirely re-examined preferences,
	saved in ENVARC:.
	Toolbars external or interns (including in the center of the principal
	window).
	New scripts @{"CmpDrawers" LINK CmpDrawers.AmiDisk}, @{"CopyNewer" LINK CopyNewer.AmiDisk}, @{"Makedir" LINK Makedir.AmiDisk}.
	Management of the buttons re-examined.
	Removal of the menus Lists and Commands.
	Translation of the english guide (using BabelDoc).

Version 1.06	April 2007
	New functions @{"REQCOLS" LINK REQCOLS}, @{"COLSIZE" LINK COLSIZE}, @{"COLUMNS" LINK COLUMNS}, columns width can now be
	saved in prefrences.
	Crash when entering data in prefs button requester removed.
	The guide has been partially translated to english.
	New PREFS argument to load a special prefs file at startup.
	Import/Export of classes, actions, macros and buttons.

Version 1.05	January 2007
	Recompilation of the program using GCC 4.0.2
	Sort of files in lists changed (no difference between
	upper and lower case)
	New ARexx interface and macro-commands, user menus,
	programmables keys and buttons...
	Classes and actions changed (actions are now "globals").

Version 1.04	March 2006
	Addition management wheel of the mouse.
	Management of the positioning of the vertical elevators on the lists.
	Correction bug comments treatment on ALL the selected files.
	Addition of a button in the preferences to decontaminate
	the bubbles of assistance.
	Correction of a bug (seized of a way in the cells determining
	those when the tab is not active).

Version 1.03	December 2005
	Addition button conditional displacement.
	Small addition @{"Copy to clipboard" LINK CopyClip}.
	Addition buttons Importation and Export in the preferences of the classes.
	Improvement of the management of the files into hexadecimal: treatment
	of the large files corrected, addition of a button seeks.
	Management of the keys spaces (passage of the window in the foreground),
	(run of the tabs), del (removal of the files), backspace (repertory relative),
	enter (action)...
	Addition shortened keyboards with the buttons.
	Addition of the name of the current file at the head of the tab.

Version 1.02	July 2005
	Addition bubbles of assistance to the window of the preferences.
	Addition possibility of making leave the windows the screen (AmiDisk
	screen). Recopy colors of Workbench on the AmiDisk screen.
	Addition All/Pass buttons on comments treatment.
	Addition paths preferences for the ten tabs.
	Addition colors with the buttons Copy and Infos.
	Addition management of the history for each tab.
	Treatment of the double click (with the choice of the user).

Version 1.01	June 2005
	Modif management classes (management of the character *).
	Addition button ':' (Root).
	Management improvement windows reading HEXA (thank you in Javier de las Rivas, javierdlr@jazzfree.com)
	Added button ' Comment'.
	Modification of the visualization on the active side (addition bars source/destination).
	Addition bars selection with the top of the list of the files.
	Addition of the guide and the management of the assistance, plus bubbles
	of assistance on the various buttons.
	Suppression bug cooling windows after change of mode of screen.
	Addition of an adjustment of the size of the plug of copy (32k by defect).
	Addition logo (thank you with HUNOPPC <nouvel.hugues@wanadoo.fr>).

Version 1.00	May 2005
	First version, written for 4.0 system.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Amťliorations" "POSSIBLE IMPROVEMENTS"
@TOC MAIN

    The following improvements will be made if the need is felt some and
    if I have time of them (and also if I have courage of it!) :
	- to finish this guide (preferences in particular),
	- improvement of the error messages, some time vague,
	- to use the notification to update the tabs in an automatic way,
	whatever the intervention made on one their entries,
	- to choose the number of tabs in the preferences.
@ENDNODE
